<DOCNO> APW20000828.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Minnesota Zoo director plans to bring NYC wow appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   APPLE VALLEY, Minn. (AP) - The new director of the Minnesota Zoo
has a mission: to bring some New York dazzle to the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Ehmke comes to Minnesota on the heels of his success with a
$50 million Congo Gorilla Forest exhibit at the Bronx Zoo in New
York, one of the most highly acclaimed new zoo exhibits in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Zoo was cutting-edge when it opened 22 years ago.
By today's standards, though, the place lacks sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't agree more that we need exhibits with a bit more
wow appeal,'' Ehmke said. ''We need to be more interactive, to get
you closer to the animals, to make use of all of the technological
and design concepts available.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehmke, due to start work Monday, said the Minnesota Zoo has a
lot to build on but could use some work. The zoo's vast undeveloped
acreage, he said, makes it ''one of most beautiful palettes a zoo
designer could ever think of working with.''
</P>
<P>
   But the zoo as it exists today, he said, is outdated, difficult
to navigate and too modest about the work it does in protecting
habitat for wild animals worldwide, including its work on behalf of
tigers in Sumatra and rhinos in Java.
</P>
<P>
   Ehmke was responsible for the Bronx Zoo's year-old Congo
exhibit, hailed by Time magazine as ''magnificent'' and
''astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The theater that is Congo wows you right to your bone,'' said
the Bronx Zoo's director, Richard Lattis. ''I mean, below the skin
to the bones that support you. You feel the vibrations, and you
never forget them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehmke, he added, led the effort and did it well enough that,
when Minnesota came knocking, Lattis offered to make him the Bronx
Zoo's assistant director.
</P>
<P>
   ''But he could not resist the challenge of going to Minnesota,''
Lattis said.
</P>
<P>
   At 42, Ehmke already has led two distinct lives, and zoo
officials consider both of them assets. First he was an
environmental lawyer, working for the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Then he trained as a landscape architect and became an expert in
how to construct zoo exhibits to make them more involving, even
theatrical, than merely plopping an animal down on a piece of land
and hoping for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Congo exhibit is incredible,'' Minnesota Zoo Board
chairman Peter Myers said. ''It really gives you a sense of what
the best exhibit design can do. No. 1, you are really unaware of
any man-made structures. All materials seem very native to that
type of environment, as opposed to a big brick or concrete
building. You feel like you're in a whole different land, and
especially not in the middle of the Bronx. And it really gives a
vivid multisensory experience - steam, sound effects, waterfalls.
It's just very creative.
</P>
<P>
   ''What drives Lee is conservation, but he understands the
realities of marketing, finance and making something attractive and
appealing to people.''
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, Ehmke's biggest job will be to lead a team to
create a new master plan for the zoo, one that both updates what's
there and that considers what to do with the 100 acres or more that
could be developed in the decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   A hundred acres is a lot, considering what Ehmke did in New York
on just six.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Zoo: http://www.mnzoo.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 0116 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Questions in Botched Israeli Raid  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASSIRA ASHMALIA, West Bank (AP) -- The mission was to take a
dangerous Islamic militant out of circulation, and it was
accomplished -- although nothing went as planned.
</P>
<P>
   After a nighttime shootout in this hillside village, Mahmoud Abu
Hanoud escaped, wounded and bleeding, to a Palestinian checkpoint,
where he surrendered before dawn Sunday. If the Israeli operation
had gone as planned, Abu Hanoud would be dead or in Israeli hands.
</P>
<P>
   Either of those possibilities could have set off waves of
Palestinian demonstrations or violence, just before President
Clinton arrives in the area to try to push Israel and the
Palestinians over the last hurdle to peace.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Hanoud is at the top of Israel's most-wanted list. They say
he was responsible for suicide bomb attacks in downtown Jerusalem
in 1997 that killed 21 and wounded dozens, as well as more recent
attacks. They have been searching for him for years.
</P>
<P>
   They found him late Saturday. A special unit of the Israeli army
moved into the village. Abu Hanoud opened fire first, then ran,
escaping the Israeli cordon.
</P>
<P>
   By nighttime Sunday, he was in jail. Col. Jibril Rajoub, the
Palestinian security chief in the West Bank, was furious with
Israel for not coordinating with him, and said such operations were
better left to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Israelis made a mistake and paid the price,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Three Israeli soldiers were killed in the exchange and another
wounded. Calling it a ''serious operational blunder,'' a grim
Israeli army chief of staff Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz admitted that all
four might have been shot by fellow soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Tibi, an Israel Arab legislator close to the Palestinian
leadership, said it was almost a blessing that the operation was
botched -- a dead Abu Hanoud might have prompted the kind of bloody
revenge attacks that have halted the peace process in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Israeli public should be thankful,'' Tibi told Israel
television. ''If he was killed there would have been a string of
attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Israeli forces shot and killed two Hamas militants in
the Hebron area, and in 1996, a top Hamas bombmaker died when a
booby-trapped mobile phone exploded in his hand. Both operations
set off rioting in the West Bank and Gaza, as Palestinians adopted
the militants as fallen heroes in the cause of freedom. The 1996
killing prompted a series of suicide bomb attacks on buses that
brought the peace process to a standstill.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers accepted the capture of Abu Hanoud by Palestinian
forces calmly, though the effect is likely to be critical -- the
last notable Hamas commander is out of circulation, dealing a blow
to an organization that opposes peace with Israel but has been
unable to mount a serious terror attack against Israel for more
than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers were the first to die in the West Bank since
January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials admit that a large-scale terror attack might
well end peace efforts, as Israel and the Palestinians tackle the
last and toughest issues before agreement. Clinton is due in Cairo
Tuesday to discuss Egyptian ideas about the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thank God he defeats the Jews,'' wailed Abu Hanoud's mother,
Fatma, 55, encircled by cheering villagers after she visited her
son in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very proud of Mahmoud Abu Hanoud because he acts
against the Zionists, the occupiers, to get our rights,'' said
Bashar Yassin, 34, an economist with the Palestinian Authority,
standing next to a pile of rubble, all that remained from the house
near the olive grove where the armed clash took place.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli forces bulldozed the house, though villagers said Abu
Hanoud was never inside. Shrugging his shoulders, Hashem Sholi, 46,
a member of the village council, said, ''That is the way of the
occupation. They must get out,'' he added, ''and they must
apologize.''
</P>
</TEXT>
