<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Record-Tying Dry Spell Hits Texas  </HEADLINE>
By KELLIE B. GORMLY
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- This summer's dry spell in North Texas became one
for the record books Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 50 years since the state last went 58 consecutive days
without measurable rainfall. With no noteworthy rain on Sunday, the
region tied that record, and forecasts showed it likely would break
it on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The current dry spell began July 1, and more heat and sunshine
are forecast for the region, said Joe Harris, a meteorologist with
the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, agriculture and livestock producers estimate they've
already lost $595 million this year due to the parched conditions,
Texas Agriculture Commissioner Susan Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   The drought has taken a toll on private lawns and gardens as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Cora Lee Brannon said her prized impatiens and begonias and even
one of her oak trees have shriveled up and died this month on her
property in the Fort Worth suburb of Southlake.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mother nature is not kind in Texas,'' she said. ''Like
everybody, it's been a struggle to keep the spring things alive. It
just doesn't make any sense to try to keep them alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite two months without rain, the region is only about a half
inch below normal for the year thanks to heavy rains in June,
Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas has received 21.19 inches of rain since Jan. 1; the
average rainfall for that time period is 22.31 inches.
</P>
<P>
   The day count for the current drought will continue until rain
is measured at the agency's rain gauge at the Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   But the state's recovery from the drought could take a year or
more as the reservoirs refill and soil slowly recharges with
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's kind of like sliding down a hill,'' Harris said.
''Eventually, you get to the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service: http://www.nws.noaa.gov
</P>
