<HEADLINE> Dutch Airliner Loses Parts in Air  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A Royal Dutch airliner carrying 449 people
dumped fuel over the ocean Sunday to make an emergency landing
after losing parts of the plane during the flight, authorities
said. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   KLM Royal Dutch Airlines Flight 602 left Los Angeles
International Airport at 4:20 p.m. for Amsterdam, Netherlands, said
Jerry Johnston, regional operations officer with the Federal
Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''The pilot did have to come back around because of engine
problems'' and dump fuel over the ocean to reduce the plane's
landing weight, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A safe landing was reported at about 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Three aircraft parts were found at nearby Dockweiler State
Beach, police Officer Don Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Parker, an investigator for the National Transportation
Safety Board, said one of the pieces, about the size of a
dishwasher, was an exhaust nozzle from one of the four engines.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the NTSB were investigating.
</P>
<P>
   Although passengers applauded once the plane landed, they were
still shaken by the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was really scary,'' Kianoosh Kamali, who was being pushed
in a wheelchair and still visibly distraught, told a television
reporter.
</P>
</TEXT>
