<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 34 As Nasdaq Rises 5  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher Monday, a possible
indication that investors are more confident about the future
direction of stock prices after several days of indecision.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 34.59 at 11,227.22.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Nasdaq composite
index was up 5.34 at 4,048.02, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
up 3.41 at 1,509.87, and the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies was up 1.38 at 526.49.
</P>
<P>
   Markets fluctuated last week, while mostly moving higher, as
investors digested the new landscape now that interest rate hikes
seem out of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   But the move upward has lacked conviction. In part, because
energy prices remain high and labor markets tight -- both factors
that could contribute to a rise in inflation. In addition, several
sectors have warned that profits may be down in the second half of
2000.
</P>
<P>
   These dynamics could pose obstacles as the markets try to
reclaim their highs of early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slender margin on
the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.60 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.28 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.10 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
