<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 10:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinian Cops Arrest 9  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASSIRA ASHMALIA, West Bank (AP) -- Israel and Palestinian police
have arrested nine Palestinians with possible ties to a top Islamic
militant who eluded Israeli troops in a botched weekend raid of his
hideout, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The failed operation -- three soldiers were killed, possibly by
friendly fire -- prompted sharp criticism of army planning and the
secret Duvdevan (Hebrew for Cherry) undercover unit, one of
Israel's key weapons in the fight against militants.
</P>
<P>
   A series of blunders turned Saturday night's raid in the West
Bank village of Assira Ashmalia ''into something close to a
national disaster,'' military commentator Ron Ben-Ishai wrote in
the Yediot Ahronot daily Monday.
</P>
<P>
   However, a successful raid, leaving top fugitive Mahmoud Abu
Hanoud dead or in Israeli hands, might have set off a wave of
Palestinian demonstrations or violence, just before President
Clinton arrives in the Middle East to try to push Israel and the
Palestinians over the last hump before peace.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Abu Hanoud, who surrendered to Palestinian police, was
recovering from his bullet wounds at the Anglican Hospital in the
Palestinian-controlled West Bank town of Nablus. Several dozen
Palestinian policemen were deployed on rooftops Monday, and
officers searched all those entering the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The surrender of Abu Hanoud, who topped Israel's most wanted
list for several years as a leader of the armed wing of the Islamic
militant group Hamas, has placed the Palestinian Authority in a
difficult situation.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, it is committed to preventing more terror
attacks that could derail peace negotiations at a critical stage.
</P>
<P>
   However, Abu Hanoud has turned into a folk hero because he
managed to evade Israeli troops, and severe punishment of the
detainee could generate fresh support for Hamas, Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat's staunchest political rival.
</P>
<P>
   ''He (Abu Hanoud) makes me feel victorious because he defeated a
special unit of a strong army like the Israeli army,'' said
28-year-old Nablus resident Firaz Hanani. ''This makes me think
there is another way to deal with the Israelis, not only through
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooperation between the Israeli and Palestinian security
services was evident again Monday, despite earlier complaints by
Palestinian officials that Israel had not coordinated the raid in
the West Bank village of Assira Ashmalia with them.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian police arrested five Hamas activists in Nablus and
the nearby village of Talouza, according to Hamas sources, while
Israel detained four residents of Assira Ashmalia on suspicion they
have ties to Abu Hanoud.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Hanoud is to be tried by a special military tribunal,
apparently within the next few days. Late Sunday, Abu Hanoud was
transferred from the hospital to the Nablus prison, and a
Palestinian security official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said the trial was to have taken place Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   However, the prisoner, who lost a lot of blood during his
flight, was considered too weak to stand trial and was sent back to
the hospital, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief military prosecutor, Khaled Kidreh, said the
investigation has not yet been completed and that no trial date has
been set.
</P>
<P>
   Israel says Abu Hanoud was responsible for suicide bomb attacks
in downtown Jerusalem in 1997 that killed 21 and wounded dozens, as
well as more recent attacks. They have been searching for him for
years.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is unlikely Abu Hanoud will be tried in a
Palestinian court for his involvement in terror attacks. In similar
cases in the past, defendants have faced charges of damaging the
Palestinians' national interests.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Hanoud's surrender, coming three months after the capture of
Hamas bombmaker Mohammed Deif in the Gaza Strip, dealt a blow to
the group, which opposes peace with Israel but has been unable to
mount a serious anti-Israeli attack for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers were the first to die in the West Bank since
January 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 1021 </TRAILER>
