<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 10:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ga. Reps Don't Fly State Flag  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Often lost among the four flags standing
outside Rep. Cynthia McKinney's Washington office is the one that's
missing.
</P>
<P>
   In McKinney's doorway, you can find banners of the American
Stars and Stripes, the Olympic games, DeKalb County, Ga., and one
commemorating prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   But the official flag of Georgia -- the one that includes a large
Confederate X -- is nowhere to be found, even though state flags are
customary office decor for members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney and fellow Georgia Democrat John Lewis, a former civil
rights leader, choose not to display the flag because they find it
divisive. Yet it's a quiet protest -- one that was never really
announced.
</P>
<P>
   If asked, they'll share their opinions that the banner should be
redrawn, that the current version was adopted in 1956 as an act of
racist defiance against school desegregation rulings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should be laid to rest,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes down to it, Lewis and McKinney know the matter
is out of their hands. They're reluctant to carry the cause much
further and are perfectly willing to leave it up to the Democratic
governor and Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ''As of now, I don't plan to get up there and fight,'' Lewis
said. ''I'll fight on an individual level for myself, and the day
may come when it may be needed for me to play a much more involved
role. But there's very little we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some critics of the state flag contend that now is
the perfect time to take aim. After all, it's an election year, and
the Confederate banner over South Carolina's Capitol created quite
a stir when George W. Bush and John McCain went to that state in
pursuit of the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only Georgia and Mississippi feature the Confederate emblem
on their official flags -- and it's much larger on Georgia's.
</P>
<P>
   The other 11 members of the state's Congressional delegation
display the flag, including Democratic Rep. Sanford Bishop, who
like McKinney and Lewis is black. Bishop declined to answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
   The flag was also one of the first pieces of decoration that
arrived at the Washington office of Democrat Zell Miller, appointed
last month to fill the Senate vacancy left by the death of
Republican Paul Coverdell.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, a former two-term governor, almost lost his re-election
bid after leading an unsuccessful crusade in 1993 to change the
flag. Now he faces another campaign in November against former Sen.
Mack Mattingly for the right to finish the four years left on
Coverdell's term.
</P>
<P>
   A poll by Georgia State University earlier this year indicates
the flag issue could be political poison. In that poll, 56 percent
wanted to keep it the way it was, and only 31 percent wanted to
change it.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might be the right thing to do. But if there's not a lot of
public support behind you, it's the sort of thing politicians would
like to avoid,'' Michael Binford, a Georgia State political
scientist, said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans figure Georgia's Democrats are trying to have
it both ways. They argue they're trying to use the flag as a tool
to attack GOP supporters yet avoid messing with it, fearing the
wrath of voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they're serious about it, they should come up with a
formula,'' said Rep. Jack Kingston, a Republican who says he would
like the Legislature to call meetings to discuss the matter. ''The
lack of leadership is astounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingston said he suspects Democrats might be forming a
''backroom plan'' to wait until after the November elections and
then call a statewide referendum for 2002, when Gov. Roy Barnes
leaves office and a successor is chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ''That would bring out the vote and help their side,'' Kingston
said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the South Carolina primary was any indication, the matter
could be hashed out before then -- especially if Georgia lives up to
its billing as a ''battleground state.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic nominee for president,
has already criticized Bush's position not to meddle in South
Carolina's affairs. Such a fight could be headed to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   There have already been some previews.
</P>
<P>
   In March, students at Centennial High School in Fulton County
voted against flying the state flag at the building. And earlier
this month, the NCAA Executive Committee turned down calls by civil
rights group to move three upcoming Final Four basketball
tournaments out of Atlanta because of the flag.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the Georgia flag was at the center of a spat between
lawmakers in Georgia and New York. Gov. George Pataki approved its
removal from the New York Capitol, and two Georgia lawmakers
retaliated by taking down New York's flag from their Capitol
rotunda.
</P>
<P>
   One of the pranksters, Georgia Senate Minority Leader Eric
Johnson, said he expects the issue will emerge again soon -- and
once again, he'll oppose any change.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pickup trucks, deer hunting, barefoot girls and boiled peanuts
-- that's what the flag represents to the vast majority of
Georgians,'' Johnson said. ''Nobody looks at it as a symbol of
hate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 1045 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0036 </DOCNO>
