<DOCNO> APW20000828.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Compromise Sought in Burundi Talks  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS TOMLINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- In a dramatic act of brinksmanship,
Burundi's president demanded last minute changes to a power-sharing
agreement for his war-torn country even as President Clinton and
eight African leaders gathered Monday to witness the signing of the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   While the African leaders waited on stage for two hours,
President Pierre Buyoya refused to emerge until chief mediator
Nelson Mandela agreed to amend the deal that the former South
African president has pushed him to sign.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators have been working down to the last minute on a
compromise deal to establish an ethnically balanced government
joining Hutus and Tutsis, even if it stops short of bringing peace
to the central African nation.
</P>
<P>
   The main sticking point was when a three-year transition process
to democracy would begin. Buyoya demanded that no transition to
multi-ethnic rule begin until a cease-fire is signed with Hutu
rebels who have boycotted the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement now calls for the transition to begin immediately,
according to a member of the mediatiaton team, who spoke on
condition he not be named.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton arrived at the hall in Arusha, Tanzania, where the
signing was due to take place, it was not clear if the differences
had been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are hoping to sign an agreement on those issues where we
have agreed, and then begin a new process to solve the problems
that remain,'' a senior Burundian official said earlier on
condition he not be named.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiators are from seven political parties representing
the Hutu majority, 10 parties representing the Tutsi minority and
negotiators from the Tutsi-dominated government and army.
</P>
<P>
   Without a cease-fire, Buyoya will face stiff opposition back
home. He has repeatedly asked Mandela, the former South African
President, to delay an agreement until the Hutu rebels join the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela has refused, and invited Clinton and the African leaders
for the signing ceremony in a bid to force a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Many Tutsis in Burundi fear sharing power will put them at the
mercy of the Hutu majority and they will meet the same fate as
Tutsis in neighboring Rwanda. In 1994, more than 500,000 Rwandans,
mainly Tutsis, were the victims of a Hutu government-orchestrated
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in
Burundi's civil war since Tutsi paratroopers assassinated the
country's first democratically elected president, a Hutu, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Arusha peace talks have been going on for two years, and
Mandela is reportedly growing impatient. Tutsi negotiators said he
threatened to quit Sunday night when they suggested a delay in
signing the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two armed Hutu groups have boycotted the talks,
Mandela has met privately with them in South Africa. A Western
diplomat involved in the negotiations said Mandela wants to end the
unwieldy Arusha talks in order to begin a new process that would
concentrate solely on a cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Extremist Tutsi groups in Burundi have threatened to stage a
coup against Buyoya if he signs any deal without a cease-fire in
place.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Buyoya signs an agreement without a cease-fire, the Buyoya
government will be very fragile,'' said the Burundian official.
''Some groups will sign without conviction just because Clinton is
here, but later, they will make implementing an agreement very
difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunfire and tracer bullets lit the sky over Burundi's capital
Sunday night as Hutu rebels attacked a Bujumbura suburb. No report
on casualties was immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tutsi hard-liners called for a boycott of commercial
activities on Monday to protest the signing.
</P>
<P>
   Students at the University of Bujumbura, mostly Tutsis, warned
commuters that cars and buses would be stoned. The students have
been boycotting classes since last week to protest the government's
inability to curb rebel attacks and Buyoya's decision to enter an
agreement with Hutu leaders blamed for anti-Tutsi killings.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise agreement was expected to cover power sharing in
the National Assembly and the military, but the 19 parties had
reached little consensus on who would become the transitional
president. Buyoya reportedly has insisted on the job, but only
three groups support him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was expected to arrive about six hours after the signing
at the Arusha International Conference Center. He planned to
address the delegates before flying to Cairo for talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
</P>
<P>
   The exact populations of Hutus and Tutsi in Burundi is unclear,
because an ethnic census has not been carried out since the 1930s.
But there is little doubt that Hutus overwhelming dominate the
country's population of around 6 million. Most estimates, using old
data, put the split at approximately 85 percent Hutu, 14 percent
Tutsi and 1 percent Twa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
