<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Air Plane To Be Reconstructed  </HEADLINE>
By ADNAN MALIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) -- Divers dragged a battered wheel and
fragments of landing gear and engines to barges in the Persian Gulf
Monday as investigators prepared to piece together the Gulf Air
carrier that crashed off the coast of Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators want to reconstruct the plane as well as possible
to help determine why the Airbus A320 nose-dived into the Gulf on
Wednesday, said Col. James Windsor, Bahrain's civil defense chief.
All 143 people aboard the Cairo-Manama flight were killed.
</P>
<P>
   ''The plan is to retrieve all the parts of the plane
immediately,'' Windsor said. ''Small numbers of parts which are
significant to the investigations will be retrieved first.''
</P>
<P>
   The task was complicated by the shallowness of the water at the
crash site, said Chief Petty Officer Michael Stackman, a U.S. Navy
diver overseeing the technical aspects of the salvage operation
being carried out by Bahraini divers. Larger boats and ships
equipped with cranes could not be used.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, divers were to place balloons under large pieces of the
plane when the bulk of the salvaging is done Tuesday. The balloons
were to be inflated, raising the pieces slightly off the seabed.
Barges would then tow the pieces to shore.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 Coast Guard divers carried up smaller pieces Monday;
some 30 more were to be brought in Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Bahraini authorities will carry out 99 percent of the
salvage effort, while the U.S. Navy will provide technical
assistance, Windsor said.
</P>
<P>
   The salvage operation will be the final step in evidence
gathering from the wreckage site of Gulf Air Flight 072.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some 200 churchgoers attended a memorial service
Monday at Bahrain's largest church, Sacred Heart, for the crash
victims.
</P>
<P>
   ''We pray for the families of the victims, that God give them
the courage to overcome the great loss of their loved ones,'' said
Father Filicio Denize.
</P>
<P>
   Remains of one Egyptian and a British citizen were flown home
Monday, the Gulf Air press center said.
</P>
<P>
   Bahrain, which has close ties with the United States and is home
base to the U.S. Navy's 5th Fleet, appointed investigator Frank
Hilldrup, of the U.S. National Transportation Safety Board, as the
chief investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have not yet received information from the black
boxes -- flight data and cockpit voice recorders -- which were
retrieved hours after the crash and could provide crucial
information in pinpointing why the airliner crashed.
</P>
<P>
   The recorders were sent to NTSB headquarters in Washington for
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim al-Hamer, chairman of the investigating committee, said
Sunday that the boxes appeared to be in good shape and that his
team had not ruled out any possible causes.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators hope to learn what happened between the time pilot
Ihsan Shakeeb aborted his landing at Bahrain International Airport
without explanation and 60 seconds later, when the plane hit the
sea.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Air's chief pilot, Hameed Ali, has said the speed and
altitude of Shakeeb's aborted landing would be investigated. He
added that no error was spotted in Shakeeb's approach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 1139 </TRAILER>
