<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Parliament Opposes Peace Deal  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- An absolute majority of Israel's parliament
told Prime Minister Ehud Barak Monday that he has no moral
authority to sign a peace deal with the Palestinians since he leads
a minority government.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has said he plans to complete a peace deal and let the
people approve it in a referendum or a quickly called election,
over the head of the parliament. Hard-line opponents admitted that
this tactic probably would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Israel and the Palestinians are closer than ever to reaching a
peace agreement, though the remaining issues, including the status
of Jerusalem, are so emotion-ridden that they could scuttle it.
Breaking with past Israeli policy, Barak offered the Palestinians
some control over parts of Jerusalem, infuriating the hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmaker Benny Elon of the hawkish National Union party on
Monday called the house into special session during its summer
recess to present a list of 62 of the 120 members of parliament who
favor a law banning a minority government from signing treaties.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest blow to Barak's prestige. Last month, his
candidate for the largely symbolic presidency lost in a Knesset
vote to the opposition candidate, and the parliament passed a bill
calling for a debate on early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the recess, Elon was prevented from proposing his
measure as a law. ''This is a demonstration,'' co-sponsor Reuven
Rivlin of the hardline Likud opposition party said.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkish parties pulled out of Barak's coalition government over
concessions to the Palestinians at last month's summit at the U.S.
presidential retreat, Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Elon told the parliament that he fears Barak ''will pull a fast
one and sign an agreement with the Palestinians during the
recess,'' which lasts until the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   His bill would ban minority governments from signing pacts that
change Israel's borders or relinquish territory. ''They can sign
agreements about selling bananas,'' said Elon's spokesman, Pini
Ben-Or.
</P>
<P>
   Elon stated his real concern in the explanation attached to his
three-paragraph bill. If a government signed a peace treaty, he
wrote, ''it would be very difficult for a future government to
shake it off.'' Ben-Or said the people could be cajoled into
backing an agreement by the argument that turning it down would
''make Israel look bad in the eyes of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Barak's coalition now represents only a third of the
house, the opposition has been unable to bring his government down
in a vote of no confidence, which requires a majority of at least
61.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Elon's proposal, Justice Minister Yossi Beilin
said Israel's election system is to blame. Israelis vote separately
for prime minister and parliament, setting up the present situation
in which a minority government can rule for months or years but
cannot pass legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''The system is a curse,'' said Beilin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 1512 </TRAILER>
