<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Postal Clerks Are Getting a New Look  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Things will look a bit different at post
offices, where clerks are getting new uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The blue-gray striped blouses and shirts become official wear on
Sept. 1, but some clerks are already sporting the new look.
</P>
<P>
   Workers will wear either navy blue or gray slacks or skirts, and
the uniforms include new neckwear too. For women the blue-gray
striped top will come with navy blue knotted loop neckwear with a
red USPS logo, or red-white-and-blue stripes.
</P>
<P>
   Men will have navy ties with a red USPS logo in a pin-dot style
or red-white-blue striped ties.
</P>
<P>
   Clerks receive an allowance to purchase their uniforms and can
buy extra garments if they wish.
</P>
<P>
   Postal officials said they were replacing the older white and
blue shirts to improve the professional image of the clerks.
</P>
<P>
   Additions to the new look are planned in the future, including:
</P>
<P>
   --Red box-stitched oxford shirt in short and long sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   --Red knit short sleeve shirt with navy blue trim.
</P>
<P>
   --Two navy knit cardigan sweaters, long sleeved or sleeveless
vest.
</P>
<P>
   --Men's navy or coordinated vest and pleated blue or gray pants.
</P>
<P>
   --Women's navy coordinates including over-top, vest and
tunic-vest with blue or gray pleated pants, skirt, pleated skirt
and an A-line jumper.
</P>
<P>
   The uniform for letter carriers is not changing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
