<HEADLINE> TV veteran joins Spanish-language television station  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - J.J. Gonzalez, who spent nearly three decades at
WCBS-TV, has been named managing editor of ''Noticias 41,'' the
awarding-winning news program of Spanish-language Univision 41
television.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is a pioneer who paved the way for hundreds of Latino
journalists not only here in New York but in the entire nation,''
Univision 41 News Director Steve Malave said in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez officially starts at Univision on Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   While at WCBS-TV, from 1967 to 1995, Gonzalez held various
posts, including reporter, assignment editor, correspondent and
director of public service programming. During that time he won
five Emmy Awards, two Associated Press journalism awards, the NYPD
Finest Award for Crime Reporting, the Bobby Kennedy Award for Crime
Reporting and the UNESCO Humanitarian Award.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving WCBS, Gonzalez worked for two years as press
secretary to Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer. Since 1997,
he has worked with cable TV's Bronxnet Community Programming Corp.,
as a consultant and then as news director.
</P>
<P>
   He currently also is an adjunct professor in the multilingual
journalism department of Lehman College. He is the author of two
novels, ''A Gull Against the Wind'' and ''A Run of Dolphins.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 1536 </TRAILER>
