<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton-bashing restaurateur softening  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SKANEATELES, N.Y. (AP) - Local restauranteur John Angyal makes
no apology for being a Clinton-basher but even he admitted he may
have crossed the line of good taste with his latest swipe at
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Angyal captured national attention last year during the first
family's vacation in this Finger Lakes resort village when he began
selling a special bologna sandwich named after Clinton, who is
running for U.S. Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   With the bologna sandwich joke getting ''a little stale,''
Angyal put up a red-lettered sign in front of his ''Johnny Angel's
Heavenly Hamburgers'' in anticipation of the Clintons' return this
weekend: ''Hillary Chicken Dinner ... $4.95. Two small breasts, two
left wings and two large thighs.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Clintons, who arrive Friday, won't see the sign. Angyal
has taken it down.
</P>
<P>
   ''This very nice lady called,'' Angyal explained, ''and she
said, 'I think the chicken dinner sign's a little tacky' and asked
if I could take it down.''
</P>
<P>
   Angyal suspects the caller was a campaign staffer for Clinton
but neither her staff nor White House officials said they knew
anything about the call.
</P>
<P>
   The woman asked if Angyal had grandchildren, and when he said
yes, she promised to send some White House souvenirs. When she hung
up, Angyal tried to trace the call, but the connection was
unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   As for the chicken dinner sign, Angyal was already being prodded
to nix it by another influential person - his wife of 40 years,
Betty.
</P>
<P>
   ''She didn't like it either,'' he said. ''The reference to
women's body parts was probably not a nice thing to put up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after he talked to the mystery caller, a package arrived
with a set of Millennium 2000 White House goblets, a hat that says
''Air Force One/Marine One,'' some White House food service shot
glasses, some presidential M&AMP;M candies, and play sets with
miniature airplanes, helicopters, black limousines and Jeeps
emblazoned with Secret Service, Air Force One and other
presidential logos.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The caller) was probably right for the most part,'' Angyal
said. ''But a lot of people loved that sign. I've never heard so
many guttural laughs from women.''
</P>
<P>
   A former town supervisor, Angyal often posts signs expressing
his irritation with local government officials. He says the signs
are all in jest.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to hurt the Clintons' feelings,'' said Angyal,
who wears a cartoon-Hillary wristwatch that flips the logo on her
baseball cap every 10 seconds from NY to AR and DC.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't support them politically, but I admire their tenacity
and stick-to-itiveness.''
</P>
</TEXT>
