<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NJ--Mock Hijackings, Bjt,600  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   POMONA, N.J. (AP) - A jumbo jet donated to the Federal Aviation
Administration was put to quick use Monday, playing host to a pair
of mock hijackings that gave a rare glimpse of anti-terrorism
agents at work.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrations, which took place on a runway at the FAA's
William J. Hughes Research Center, featured members of the
government's Federal Air Marshals program, which trains agents in
SWAT-style techniques and sends them anonymously onto passenger
airliners.
</P>
<P>
   Established in 1985, after the two-weeklong hijacking of a TWA
jet by Shiite Muslims in Beirut, Lebanon, the program provides
armed agents for deployment all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   It has headquarters here, where agents train on outdoor shooting
ranges, an aircraft simulator, a five-story air traffic control
center and two airplanes during their 14-week training courses.
</P>
<P>
   FAA officials won't say how many agents participate in the
program, citing security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The jumbo jet, a wide-body Delta Air Lines L-1011, was signed
over Monday by Delta officials. FAA officials said the plane - the
first jumbo jet made available to the program - would provide a
realistic backdrop for training.
</P>
<P>
   Its engines will be removed, and it will take up permanent
residence on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   ''People have to train in circumstances as realistic as
possible,'' said Cathal Flynn, an FAA security administrator.
''It's going to be enormously valuable to us and the program to
have a wide-body aircraft on which to practice our tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing demonstrations, on board the L-1011, showed how
federal agents respond to in-flight crises - both major and minor.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, FAA officials and members of the news media
boarded the jet and donned protective headgear before the hijacking
attempt began aboard ''Flight 777 to Istanbul.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a hijacking!'' one of the captors shouted, jumping out
of his seat in first class and pulling the pin on a hand grenade.
''It's our plane now! Stay down!'' he yelled at the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Another captor strolled the aisles, threatening them. ''What are
you looking at? Get down! Eyes down!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, federal agents leaped out of their seats and
fired shots at the grenade carrier, overtaking him. ''We are the
police,'' one called out to passengers afterward. ''Stay in your
seats. Do not move.''
</P>
<P>
   The second scenario involved a knife-wielding attacker
attempting a hijacking. He, too, was ''shot'' by agents, who fired
blanks so nobody on board was injured.
</P>
<P>
   The third showed a passenger being knocked to the ground and
handcuffed after assaulting a flight attendant. The fourth showed
agents subduing a drunken passenger who was escorted to the rear of
the aircraft by an agent because he was being disruptive.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the most typical incidences these days, according to
Doug, one of the agents, who could not be identified because of his
work.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're there to assist (stewards and attendants) if it gets
physical,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mac Armstrong, executive vice president for Delta, said the
airline was happy to donate the jet, which could have fetched up to
$3 million if sold for its parts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We know the security and safety of the world's skies is not
just a Delta issue or an FAA issue. It affects all of us, all the
governing agencies and the flying public,'' Armstrong said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administration: www.faa.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 1605 </TRAILER>
