<DOCNO> APW20000828.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Some Reluctant Tutsis Sign Deal  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS TOMLINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- After being chastised by Nelson Mandela,
half of Burundi's Tutsi politicians reluctantly signed a
power-sharing agreement Monday, but hamstrung it with reservations
that ensured the deal could not be implemented without extensive
renegotiations.
</P>
<P>
   While President Clinton looked on before the official signing,
the former South African rebel leader and president gave an
impassioned speech, condemning any group that refused to
participate in the power-sharing agreement that his mediators had
drafted.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement called for a balance between Tutsis and Hutus in
the government, National Assembly and military as well as a
three-year transition to democratic elections.
</P>
<P>
   While all the parties representing the Hutu majority signed the
agreement, only four out of 10 Tutsi political parties signed, as
well as President Pierre Buyoya and a representative of the army.
While the most important Tutsi parties signed, the failure to reach
a consensus cast a shadow over the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Something disturbing has occurred,'' Mandela warned at the
beginning of a fiery speech that invoked his personal experiences
in the struggle against apartheid in South Africa. ''I don't think
there are many countries where leaders have undermined an agreement
which they had solemnly made.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela had hoped to complete a comprehensive peace agreement
Monday, with Clinton and the leaders of eight African countries
looking on. But the refusal of two Hutu rebel groups to join the
talks meant that only a political agreement was possible.
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people, mostly civilians, have died since
Tutsi paratroopers assassinated Burundi's first and only
democratically elected president, a Hutu, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Buyoya, a retired paratrooper who took power in a 1996 coup, and
the group of 10 Tutsi parties had demanded an extension of Monday's
deadline for an agreement, but Mandela refused, saying that two
years of negotiations had been enough.
</P>
<P>
   The Burundi president has been under intense pressure not to
sign a deal without a cease-fire from the rebels. Some extremist
Tutsi groups had threatened a coup if he did so.
</P>
<P>
   Many Tutsis in Burundi fear sharing power will put them at the
mercy of the Hutu majority and they will meet the same fate as
Tutsis in neighboring Rwanda. In 1994, more than 500,000 Rwandans,
mainly Tutsis, were the victims of a Hutu government-orchestrated
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's limited signing took place only after last-minute
brinkmanship by Burundi's leaders. Mandela, the African leaders and
the Hutu parties took the stage for a signing ceremony before
Clinton's arrival. But none of the Tutsi parties, nor Buyoya, would
come out, leaving the ceremony waiting for two hours before Ugandan
President Yoweri Museveni announced a delay.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been in the labor room waiting for the baby to be born
and the labor is taking a little longer than expected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours later, when Mandela and Clinton took the stage, the
Tutsi parties were still not present, though Buyoya sat stone-faced
in the back row. Mandela then went into a scathing speech,
condemning those who would not sign, but not mentioning them by
name.
</P>
<P>
   ''Another group, representing mainly the Tutsi community, a
minority of 14 percent in Burundi, forgot about the agreement. They
wanted to leave open almost everything. They refused to sign,''
Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton was making his remarks, though, the leaders of the 10
Tutsi parties took their seats while the president compared the
Burundi peace process to others he has worked on around the world.
He warned the delegates against not implementing the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you come back in five or ten years, will the issues have
changed, I think not,'' Clinton said. ''The gulf between you won't
narrow, but the gulf between you and the rest of the world, I
assure you, will grow wider.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, a Tutsi spokesman announced to the ceremony that some
Tutsi parties would not sign, while others would sign with
reservations that could only be resolved with further negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Nsanze, leader of the African-Burundaise Alliance for
Salvation, said the Tutsi parties had reservations with the
document's title and every other substantive issue addressed in the
document.
</P>
<P>
   ''What this means is that with these signatures and these
reservations, there can be no implementation until these issues are
solved,'' Nsanze said.
</P>
<P>
   While the power-sharing agreement was touted by participants as
an important step forward, it also failed to address the key issue
of when a cease-fire would take place.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela has held private meetings with the Hutu rebel leaders in
South Africa, and came out in support of their position that no
cease fire was possible without a power-sharing agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
