<HEADLINE> Iran Clash Leave Police Officer Dead  </HEADLINE>
By ALI AKBAR DAREINI
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) -- Hard-line vigilantes clashed with reformist
students in western Iran, leaving a policeman dead, Iran's
state-run radio and a student leader said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The clashes, which began Thursday and reached a climax Sunday,
injured 25 to 30 students in the city of Khorramabad, about 300
miles southwest of Tehran, student leader Amir Hussein Balali told
The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontations put an end to a democracy seminar -- slated to
end Wednesday after a week -- when local authorities told student
organizers Sunday they could no longer guarantee security for the
sessions, Balali said.
</P>
<P>
   Rioting broke out Sunday night after the clashes between the
vigilantes and members of the Office for Fostering Unity, the
student group, Balali said after returning to Tehran. He did not
say how many students took part in the clashes and riots.
</P>
<P>
   ''Police officer Ardeshir Karami was killed Sunday evening
during clashes with opportunists and rioters who smashed windows of
shops causing damages to public and private properties,'' Tehran
Radio said.
</P>
<P>
   Balali, said: ''We heard that a police officer was killed in the
riots.''
</P>
<P>
   The democracy seminar opened on Wednesday with a message from
reformist President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
   But Brig. Gen. Gholam-Reza Soleimani, a top officer of the elite
Revolutionary Guards in the region, warned in remarks published
Saturday of a ''crushing response'' if the seminar continued.
</P>
<P>
   After the seminar's close, the daily Hayat-e-Now quoted leading
reformist lawmaker, Ali Shakouri-Rad, as saying Monday: ''If the
establishment cannot provide security for a legal gathering, then
it has violated the philosophy of its existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Balali said armed Revolutionary Guards and police were present
during the clashes but did not intervene to stop the
confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time since July that hard-liners used violence
to silence reformists, who are calling for easing social and
political restrictions by hard-line Islamic authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Balali said that some 200 vigilantes and armed Revolutionary
Guards surrounded Khorramabad airport over the weekend and
prevented leading reformist thinkers Abdolkarim Soroush and Mohsen
Kadivar of Tehran University from leaving the station to address
the seminar. It said the two returned to Tehran.
</P>
</TEXT>
