<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New curriculum developed to teach about Connecticut Indians  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many schoolchildren, the only formal lessons about American
Indians arrive at Thanksgiving time, when the story of the Pilgrims
and the Indians gets its annual airing.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut students are now able to probe deeper into the
history of eastern tribes with the development of a curriculum
guide for teachers from kindergarten to high school.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-page guide, created through an act of the Legislature
three years ago, tells Connecticut Indian history from the Indian
point-of-view.
</P>
<P>
   Similar teaching guides are being developed about the Irish
Potato Famine and the experiences of blacks and Puerto Ricans in
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   An advisory board including historians and educators from some
Connecticut tribes helped put together the lesson guide.
</P>
<P>
   The guide is the first step toward a greater understanding of
local Indian history, said Trudie Lamb Richmond, a Schaghticoke
Indian who is the program manager for education at the Mashantucket
Pequot Museum and Research Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Generally, the focus has been on west of the Mississippi.
Although we talk a little bit about the Pilgrims, then history
seems to take a great quantum leap,'' said Richmond, who advised
the state Department of Education on the guide.
</P>
<P>
   Guide author Kathleen Hunter said teachers can use the program
to include the American Indian experience in their lessons on
different periods in history.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we've tried to do is show how there still are native
Americans in Connecticut, as we all now know, and things were going
on related to native American affairs throughout Connecticut's
history,'' said Hunter, the director of education for the Old State
House in Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   The guide gives basic information about Connecticut tribes, from
before European colonization to the present day, and suggests
lessons appropriate for different ages.
</P>
<P>
   The guide includes the traditional creation stories of the
tribes, as a counterpoint to the prevailing scientific theory that
people came to the Americas from Asia, over a land bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The guide also includes the Indian perspective on colonization,
wars with the English, missionaries who tried to convert Indians to
Christianity and political attempts to assimilate tribes into
European society.
</P>
<P>
   Stories from Connecticut Indian history are compared with
similar stories from other cultures. For example, one lesson
suggests comparing Shakespeare's ''Romeo and Juliet'' to the story
of two Cherokee boys who attended an Indian school in Cornwall and
married white girls, to the dismay of white people in Cornwall and
Cherokee families in the South.
</P>
<P>
   In helping put together the guide, Richmond recalled her own
education in the 1950s in western Connecticut and the reception she
got from her teacher when she proposed an essay on Indian history
as part of a multicultural presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ''She said, 'Oh, Trudie, Indians haven't made sufficient
contributions. You really have to pick another group.''' Richmond
recalled. ''I was just floored. ... That must have been my goal
from then on, that I was going to show what native people have
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Fawcett, the Mohegans' tribal historian, said she hoped
the guide will revive an interest in state and local history.
</P>
<P>
   ''Local history curriculum sometimes gets pushed aside because
everyone's preparing for standardized tests. This is one way we
hope can create an easy, flexible mix so teachers still find time
to teach local history,'' Fawcett said.
</P>
<P>
   The guide ''Native Americans of Connecticut - Holding On and
Moving Forward'' does not delve into contemporary issues such as
federal recognition of tribes and Indian-run casinos, although
these issues are raised as topics for discussion for older
students.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state Department of Education really does not want to get
into the position of being for or against casinos, so what it can
do is recommend issues to discuss,'' Hunter explained.	   The state law that
created these teaching guides do not mandate
that they be used in the classroom. The Indian history guide was
completed and distributed a few weeks ago, so it may take time for
the material to make it into classrooms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
