<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruff Says He Didn't Discuss E-mail  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID HO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former White House counsel Charles Ruff said
Monday he never spoke with President Clinton or his senior aides
about an e-mail foul-up that kept his staff from properly reviewing
messages under subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   At a court hearing on the missing e-mails, Ruff said he couldn't
recall discussing the e-mail problem outside of his own staff and a
conversation with White House lawyer Mark Lindsay. Ruff presented
similar testimony before a congressional committee in May.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials earlier this year said thousands of
e-mails, including some from Vice President Al Gore's office, were
not properly archived. As a result, White House lawyers never
reviewed the messages to determine if they should be turned over to
investigators probing cases ranging from the Monica Lewinsky
scandal and Whitewater to campaign fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff, a former Watergate prosecutor and U.S. attorney for the
District of Columbia, said he wasn't sure how he first learned of
the e-mail problem in June 1998, but it was either from Lindsay or
from a copy of a memo sent to John Podesta, President Clinton's
chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Reprising his testimony from May, Ruff said he didn't advise
senior aides of the problem because it didn't appear to be that
serious at first.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I had known the full scope of it, I certainly would have
discussed it with Mr. Podesta,'' Ruff said.
</P>
<P>
   The computer problems became public only last February, in a $90
million class-action suit filed by the conservative Judicial Watch,
which has filed several lawsuits against Clinton since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth has been holding hearings for
several weeks to determine how to retrieve the messages.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch general counsel Larry Klayman said outside the
courthouse that he wasn't satisfied with Ruff's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ''He came in and he had no memory,'' Klayman said. ''He was not
candid to this court.''
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch also wants to question Podesta and attorney
Virginia Apuzzo, the former assistant to the president for
management and administration.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay testified last Wednesday that e-mails lost in 1998 were
the victims of an ''antiquated and unstable'' computer system that
crashed repeatedly. He said the system was upgraded in 1999 to head
off expected Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay said he told Ruff and Podesta, then the deputy chief of
staff, about the e-mail glitch in June 1998 but he also never spoke
to Clinton about the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Former White House employee Sheryl Hall, who first unearthed the
e-mail problem, alleged in a declaration that ''when the
contractors told the White House about the problem, they were
threatened, warned not to discuss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ruff and Lindsay deny that they threatened anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Judicial Watch has accused White House officials of acting to
delay production of the e-mails until after November's election.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail investigation is part of a larger lawsuit over FBI
background files gathered in the White House on hundreds of
appointees from the Reagan and Bush administrations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
