<HEADLINE> Rutgers psychological clinic to offer services for Tourette patients </HEADLINE>
By HANAH CHO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Wendy Zwoboda says few resources are
available to mothers who, like her, have two kids with Tourette
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   So Zwoboda welcomes the addition of a treatment program for
Tourette patients and their families at Rutgers University's
psychological clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm definitely planning to get on board,'' said Zwoboda, a
special education teacher from Riverdale. ''How could we not? I
envision it as a one-stop shopping, like a Wal-Mart for Tourette
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The program - in conjunction with the Tourette Syndrome
Association of New Jersey - will offer individual and family
therapy, social-skill development sessions and educational
workshops at one location beginning in late September.
</P>
<P>
   Faith Rice, president of the Somerville-based organization, said
the clinic will serve as a ''central clearinghouse'' for families
looking for help and information.
</P>
<P>
   ''Tourette is not only for the individual,'' she said. ''It's
very much a family problem because it's with a child 24 hours a
day, and it's certainly with the family 24 hours a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourette Syndrome is an inherited neurological disorder
characterized by repeated involuntary facial, head, or body
movements and uncontrollable sounds called tics, such as grunting,
sniffing or barking. Some vocal tics can include inappropriate
words and phrases. Symptoms often begin in early childhood.
</P>
<P>
   When 10-year-old Adam was diagnosed with the disorder a few
years ago, Zwoboda said she didn't know where to turn for help.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a nightmarish diagnosis where they pat your head and
you have to do your own research,'' said Zwoboda, adding Adam's
twin sister, Rachael, also was diagnosed with the disorder last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Although Zwoboda found help through the association, she said
the clinic will help families find treatment and information about
the disorder without going out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Four psychology doctoral students and a program supervisor will
run the clinic's Tourette Syndrome program. The clinic is located
at the university's Busch campus in Piscataway.
</P>
<P>
   Don Morgan, the clinic's director, said the students will work
with patients to develop individualized therapy to control tics and
less-obvious symptoms such as obsessive compulsive disorder,
attention deficit disorder and learning disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   A special emphasis will be placed on social-skills development
sessions for kids, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have a hard time developing good social skills with
getting along with other kids and dealing with the stigmas,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The psychological clinic offers other outpatient services, and
fees are based on a sliding scale. For more information, call the
clinic at (732)445-6111 or the association at (732)972-4459.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.rutgerspsychservices.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.tsanj.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
