<BODY>
<HEADLINE> RETRANSMITTING to ADD referral to main story  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The exclusion of the Dalai Lama from the United
Nations for the Millennium World Peace Summit gathering of
religious leaders brought angry, yet saddened protesters on Monday
to a plaza across from the organization's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The group of about 150 Tibetan exiles, monks, and Free Tibet
activists gathered at the park to offer rebukes to the United
Nations, for what they believed to be the organization's caving
into Chinese pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Holding up signs reading ''Peace Summit Without Substance'' and
''UN: Assert Yourself,'' the crowd stood in quiet protest,
listening to monks offer prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you hear the words peace and religion in the same
sentence the Dalai Lama must immediately come to mind,'' said
Yangdon Tsering, a Tibetan exile who lives in New Jersey. ''To not
invite him is totally incongruous with what they were trying to do
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit, which runs Monday through Thursday, is hoped to
result in resolutions on peace, poverty and the environment, as
well as the formation of a permanent council of religious leaders
to advise the United Nations on preventing and settling disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The first two days of the summit were scheduled to be held at
the United Nations with the last two at the Waldorf-Astoria.
</P>
<P>
   Working on the advice of a U.N. official, conference organizers
did not invite the Dalai Lama to the first two days of the
conference for fear of offending China.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers offered the Tibetan Buddhist leader and a Nobel Peace
Prize winner an invitation to the last two days of the conference,
but he declined.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday evening it was announced that an eight-person
delegation of Tibetan Buddhist leaders had been sent by the Dalai
Lama, two of whom would be speaking in the General Assembly hall
with the understanding that their speech will not be political.
</P>
<P>
   But that did little to placate the protesters who turned their
anger on the U.N.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems that the U.N. has decided to side with the stronger
power here. They should be looking at all sides of this and make it
the goal to try harder to listen and understand the weaker side. I
thought that this was their mandate. I must have been wrong,'' said
Geshe Kelsang Monlam, a Tibetan monk, who has lived in Philadelphia
for the past 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''The U.N. is afraid of the Chinese delegation,'' scoffed Tseten
Namdol, a Tibetan exile who moved to New York from India two years
ago. ''If they back down to them here, how can they say they
believe in human rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
