<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group says it can do rebate program one better  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A public policy group that has criticized
the Whitman administration's fiscal practices now says it has a
better way to offer New Jersey taxpayers a break.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Policy Perspective wants to revamp the NJ Saver
program to dole out checks that average $926.
</P>
<P>
   But to pay for this property tax relief the group proposes
higher income taxes for individuals making more than $75,000 a year
and a new tax on financial assets.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Policy Perspective president Jon Shure says New
Jersey's property tax system forces the middle class to pay a
disproportionate share of the state tax revenues. This proposal
would make the overall tax burden fairer, said Shure, a former
communications director for Gov. Jim Florio, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   ''We ask the middle class to shoulder a higher-percentage burden
than we ask the rich, and that needs to be changed,'' Shure said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 44-page report released Monday, analysts from the group
called the property tax a ''house tax''.
</P>
<P>
   By taxing property, the state in effect taxes the only asset
many people ever own, Shure said. That allows other financial
assets owned by wealthy residents to escape a state tax levy, he
claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was a great system in the 18th century, when only the
rich had property,'' Shure said.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its second year, the NJ Saver program is expected to give
property owners a rebate of $240. The program bases the refund on a
portion of the amount of school taxes paid.
</P>
<P>
   The program is scheduled to be fully funded in three more years.
This year's rebate checks are scheduled to be mailed beginning
Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Senate President Donald T. DiFrancesco announced a
plan to fully fund that rebate next year and to increase the
Homestead Rebate.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco said the state can use expected increases in
revenues to fund his $400 million program.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most conservative estimate says the state will see an
additional $1.4 billion in new money, DiFrancesco said.
</P>
<P>
   Shure says his plan can be implemented without relying on the
promise of revenue windfalls in a growing economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's still a cross-your fingers plan. This is all paid for
right away from day one,'' Shure said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for DiFrancesco said Monday that his plan is
fiscally conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Senate president's proposal is a realistic proposal that
puts more dollars than ever back into the pockets of taxpayers,''
spokeswoman Rae Hutton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Jim Florio tried this in 1990 and we entered into the worst
recession in state history,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   To fund Shure's proposal, his group suggests increasing the
income tax and a new tax on financial assets.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would increase the income tax from 6.37 percent to 8.87
percent on those earning $75,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Assets greater than $2 million would be taxed at one-quarter of
1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 1 percent of households in the state would be
affected by the new tax, Shure said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's called asking the rich to pay their fair share,'' Shure
said.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal is not likely to become law any time soon, Shure
said. His goal is to force discussion about what he says is ''a
fundamentally flawed system.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not going to happen tomorrow. The point here is, we
need to put things like this on the table. We need to start talking
about real reforms,'' Shure said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
