<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Timor Fears More Violence  </HEADLINE>
By DANIEL COONEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, East Timor (AP) -- Schools and hospitals are open. Houses
are being built. Elections are scheduled. A year after its historic
independence vote, East Timor is literally rising from its ashes.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the ravaged territory marks the first anniversary
of the U.N.-supervised vote for independence from Indonesia that
triggered a bloody backlash by pro-Indonesia militiamen that ended
only after international forces arrived in September.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, Dili, streets that echoed with gunfire one year
ago are now alive with the noise of hammers and saws.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very happy that East Timor is free. We can start our
lives over,'' said Diamantino Chang, a college student who has
returned to classes 12 months after the local university was
wrecked.
</P>
<P>
   But there is fear behind the optimism. A new wave of violence
already threatens the dream of statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-independence militia gangs, responsible for last year's
mayhem, are infiltrating from Indonesian West Timor. While U.N.
peacekeepers have stepped up patrols and occasionally exchange
fire, they can do little to plug the mountainous 75-mile border.
Two peacekeepers have been killed and four wounded in recent
clashes; several militiamen also have died.
</P>
<P>
   ''The militia are back and want to lay waste this immense effort
to rebuild,'' said Jose ''Xanana'' Gusmao, a charismatic former
guerrilla chief who spent years in an Indonesian prison and is
likely to be the first president of an independent East Timor,
possibly within two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are still burning houses and killing people. We have to
treat them as terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gelbard, the U.S. ambassador to Indonesia, has warned of
a guerrilla war unless the militias are disbanded.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Vieira de Mello, the chief U.N. administrator of the
territory, said Monday a U.N. force may have to remain in East
Timor after it becomes independent to fend off the militia
incursions.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the present threat from the western part of the island
continues, the U.N. may have to remain involved in safeguarding
security for the Timorese,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Maj. Gen. Mike Smith, the deputy peacekeeper
commander, says the militiamen cross the border at night and force
terrified villagers to hide them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The terrain around the border is ideal for small groups who
want to remain undetected,'' he said. ''But we can apply a lot of
force against them and will pursue them to their lair.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials and aid workers complain the anti-independence
gangs control refugee camps that sprang up on the Indonesian side
of the frontier after last year's violence.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of East Timorese who fled to the camps or were forced
there by militias have now returned home. But about 80,000 remain
in the makeshift settlements, and many accuse Indonesia's military
of arming and training gangs to destabilize the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia's new democratic government has sought to mend
relations with East Timor, but concedes some rogue segments of its
army may be behind the latest trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly Muslim Indonesia invaded mainly Roman Catholic
East Timor in 1975 after Portugal suddenly ended four centuries of
colonial rule. Tens of thousands died of disease, famine and
military repression in the ensuing years that ended with last
August's independence vote.
</P>
<P>
   The international community is pressing Indonesia's government
to prosecute those responsible for the bloodshed and some suspects
are expected to be named within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many fear politically powerful army generals, accused of
orchestrating the chaos, may escape through a constitutional
loophole just passed by Indonesia's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Dili, shattered families mourn. In one tearful
commemoration, thousands marched by candlelight through the dusty
streets and prayed for those killed in the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ''He died in my arms,'' said Domingas de Jesus, whose teen-age
son was shot by Indonesian forces a few weeks before international
peacekeepers restored order.
</P>
<P>
   While most ordinary people are thankful for an end to Indonesian
rule, many independence fighters have found it hard to adjust. Some
units have not disbanded in case they are needed to counter militia
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment is running at about 70 percent. Locals rely on U.N.
handouts and some resent the comparatively high living standards of
U.N. officials and aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants and cafes have opened for free-spending foreigners
while most East Timorese struggle to survive. Some are subsistence
farmers. Others pack Dili's ramshackle market to sell anything from
counterfeit jeans to statues of the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations admits there are problems, but says it is
drafting an economic blueprint for East Timor based on coffee
exports and offshore oil and natural gas. Its pristine beaches,
soaring mountains and blend of Portuguese and indigenous cultures
also have tourism potential.
</P>
<P>
   Elections are slated for the end of 2001, and until then,
''there is much left to be accomplished,'' said U.N. chief Vieira
de Mello. ''But East Timor is irrevocably on the path to full
independence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 1720 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man gets 40 years in stabbing deaths of two teens  </HEADLINE>
By DAVE COLLINS
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Addressing the man who plunged an 8-inch
knife into her son's chest, Elizabeth Potkaj held a picture of the
slain teen and tried to convey in court the pain that devastated
her and her family.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look at his face,'' Potkaj said Monday, as tears ran down her
face. ''Look at the pain you have caused his mother. You put him in
the ground and I will never see him again. You did this to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Potkaj's comments, a Hartford Superior Court judge
sentenced 28-year-old Joseph Pranckus III to the maximum 40 years
in prison for stabbing to death 16-year-old Paul Potkaj and
18-year-old Bryan Judd, both of East Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   A jury convicted Pranckus last month of two counts of
first-degree manslaughter. The jury rejected a capital felony
charge, which carries a potential death penalty, and murder
charges, before convicting Pranckus of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Pranckus stabbed the youths during a Fourth of
July party at a Glastonbury home in 1998. Police said there was
beer and marijuana at the party.
</P>
<P>
   Pranckus maintained that he was forced to defend himself when
Potkaj, Judd and other youths confronted him as he was trying put
an end to the party. Pranckus suffered a broken eye socket and a
concussion during the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I certainly, certainly wasn't thinking about hurting
anybody,'' Pranckus told the judge. ''It was done out of fear. When
you're backed into a corner and you have four people who keep
coming after you ... I can't describe the fear that I felt. There
was no time to think. There was time to react.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I am deeply sorry,'' Pranckus said. ''I should have called the
cops. I should have had everybody arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge William L. Wollenberg said he based the sentence on a
report by the Department of Adult Probation, which conducted an
investigation for sentencing purposes after Pranckus was convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joseph Pranckus' aggressive behavior needlessly took the lives
of two young individuals,'' the report read. ''A lengthy period of
incarceration is appropriate and recommended.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Assistant State's Attorney Dennis O'Connor used that
passage from the report in his remarks to the judge.
</P>
<P>
   ''All he had to do was to think before he picked up that
knife,'' O'Connor said. ''But instead he picked up that 8-inch
knife ... and he plunged it into literally the hearts of two
teen-agers.''
</P>
<P>
   The victims' families told the judge they were disappointed with
the jury's verdict, and described how the killings hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Judd Sr., Bryan Judd's grandfather, read a letter from
Bryan's sister, Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's not too many days that go by that I don't cry,''
Shannon wrote. ''I cry for the loss of my brother and how much I
miss him. I cry for all the things he never got to do and
experience. This pain never leaves. It's an emptiness. It's an ache
that never subsides.''
</P>
<P>
   John Potkaj, Paul Potkaj's father, described the pain of losing
a child.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no greater joy than the one of a child being born,''
John Potkaj said. ''Now all the joy and the happiness have been
taken away from us. This did not have to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Public Defender Kevin Barrs said Pranckus had a
difficult childhood in which he lived in several foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the party, Pranckus was the father of a newborn
and was thinking about joining the National Guard, he said. He also
planned on learning to drive tractor trailers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want my daughter growing up questioning where I
was,'' Pranckus said, referring to his experience with his own
parents. ''I wanted to her grow up having great pride and respect
for who her father was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
