<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki panel makes recommendations on college dorm fire safety  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - All college dormitories in New York state
should undergo fire inspections at least once a year, recommends a
panel appointed by Gov. George Pataki after three college students
in New Jersey died in a dorm fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Task Force on Campus Fire Safety said the state should
rescind the exemptions to fire inspections now given to colleges in
New York City, Buffalo, Yonkers, Rochester, Syracuse and Albany.
The inspections should all be carried out by the state's Office of
Fire Prevention and Control.
</P>
<P>
   The panel was formed following the Jan. 19 fire at Seton Hall
University in New Jersey and chaired by New York Secretary of State
Alexander Treadwell. The heads of the State University and City
University of New York systems were on the task force, as was the
president of the Commission on Independent Colleges and
Universities.
</P>
<P>
   The task force also recommended:
</P>
<P>
   -Developing guidelines for training campus personnel and
students about preventing fires and how to respond when there is a
fire. Colleges are encouraged to show campus fire safety training
videos to all new students.
</P>
<P>
   -Toughening penal statutes to make tampering with fire detection
equipment or fire alarms a crime.
</P>
<P>
   -Requiring that sprinklers be installed in any new dormitories
or those buildings being ''significantly rehabilitated.''
</P>
<P>
   That last point is the biggest source of controversy in the
dormitory safety debate. While few people argue that sprinkler
systems are not the best way to fight dormitory fires, college
administrators say they simply don't have enough money to meet an
immediate state mandate for existing dormitory buildings to be
retrofitted with the devices.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Edward Sullivan, a Manhattan Democrat who
chairs his chamber's higher education committee, said it would cost
in the ''hundreds of millions of dollars'' to put sprinklers in all
existing dormitories at the more than 200 public and private
colleges in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are talking about big bucks here,'' said Sullivan, who
introduced a bill in the Assembly earlier this year requiring the
retrofitting of sprinkler systems in all dorms. It did not include
an appropriation of state money and did not pass.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically - and out of fairness - Sullivan said the state
would probably have to provide some aid to private colleges if it
requires that sprinklers be installed at both private and public
schools in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said he is writing state Assembly Speaker Sheldon
Silver to ask him to make dormitory sprinklers a priority for
receiving a significant state allocation in the 2001-02 state
budget.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Sullivan said it is important to identify the
dormitory buildings on all campuses which are candidates for
sprinkler retrofittings and make certain those buildings have the
best, and most tamper-resistant, fire alarms and fire detection
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're 21, when I was 21, you do a lot of dumb things,''
Sullivan said. ''We have to have some method (of stopping alarm
tampering) and just increasing penalties is not going to do it.
There has to be some fire alarms that cannot be deactivated, or
which sound an alarm when they are deactivated.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Trent, a spokesman for the Department of State, said a
news release detailing the report's findings was distributed and
posted on the department's Web site Friday. The fire safety report
itself was posted on the Web site Monday.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Department of State: http://www.dos.state.ny.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 1732 </TRAILER>
