<HEADLINE> Americans Warned on Lebanon Travel  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department cautioned Americans
Monday that travel to Lebanon was risky and that U.S. officials may
not be able to help them if they run into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Special care was recommended for travel in the southern suburbs
of Beirut and the Bekaa Valley. The Lebanese government does not
control Palestinian camps and they should be avoided, the travel
warning said.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are rarely targeted in Lebanon, but groups that
attacked Americans in the past are still in the country and are
still powerful, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials restrict their own travel because of security
problems. That, combined with limited staffing, may prevent the
U.S. Embassy from helping Americans in trouble, the department
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
