<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Finnish Kosovo Troops Head to Sauna  </HEADLINE>
By MERITA DHIMGJOKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIPLJAN, Yugoslavia (AP) -- After a day of patrolling, clearing
mines, or even being shot at, the troops of the Finnish Battalion
in Kosovo's peacekeeping force like to unwind -- in the sauna.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Kosovo hasn't had enough scorching days this
summer. Temperatures have topped 100 degrees several times.
</P>
<P>
   But for many Finns, saunas are stress-busters, anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ''If sauna or alcohol cannot help you with your problem, then
you have got a serious problem,'' said Maj. Teuvo Tikkanen, as he
briefed visiting reporters on the value of a good sauna. The
briefing was held outside one of 20 that were built especially for
about 800 Finnish soldiers in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   When they first arrived last August as part of the NATO-led
peacekeeping force, the soldiers set their priorities. Before they
built barracks, they erected saunas, with pine from Finland.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a form of social communication,'' said Col. Matti
Ponteva, medical director of mental health for the Finnish troops.
</P>
<P>
   ''If something critical happens during the day and you want to
discuss it with your friends, a sauna is the place to do it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the soldiers are proud of their ''saunamania.'' Finland
boasts about 2 million saunas for its 5.1 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the heat, many soldiers go to the sauna twice a day.
After that comes the next stage of the ritual -- drinking beer or
water in the small pools outside the saunas.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is normal that I will meet someone naked before I see that
person in uniform,'' said Eeva Sovnarvi, a veterinary officer, as
she sipped water before re-entering the steam room.
</P>
<P>
   While Finns say the sauna has little to do with sex, they bowed
to Kosovo's more conservative attitudes and built separate
facilities for men and women.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's so hot in there that sexual fantasies are impossible,''
Ponteva said.
</P>
<P>
   An ethnic Albanian interpreter blushed and turned away when she
was asked what she thought of the idea of sharing a bench with
others in a sauna.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's Muslim culture here, and it's difficult,'' said Sgt.
Markku Mikkonen. ''But I am getting permission for a Serb
interpreter to go to the sauna, since she said she would like to
try it once.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the therapeutic value of the daily sauna, the Finns say,
it tells others in Kosovo something about who they are.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be nice if troops from different nations brought a
piece of their country to Kosovo, just like us,'' Tikkanen said,
joking. ''The Spanish troops could organize bull fights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
