<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Building projects in southwestern NJ on hold due to water threat  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT LAUREL, N.J. (AP) - For decades, while the rest of New
Jersey was experiencing unprecedented growth, the farmland and
fields at the state's southwestern corner were largely forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Those days are over. Woods and peach orchards in Salem and
Gloucester counties are being converted into malls and housing
developments. But building plans apparently have outpaced what the
state projected, and officials aren't sure there will be enough
water to support the growth.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Protection has halted
issuing water permits for new homes in Gloucester and Salem
counties. Officials are waiting for the results of a study by the
U.S. Geological Survey on how new development will affect the
state's water supply. Those results are expected next month.
</P>
<P>
   Builders say the moratorium on permits is a rash solution to a
problem that never should have occurred. But the state and the U.S.
Geological Survey say they're trying to prevent a problem before
it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you look at the state as a whole, the state has adequate
water to meet future needs,'' Eric Evenson, district chief of the
Geologic Survey in New Jersey, said Monday, ''but there are
particular areas in the state where water is in short supply, given
future demand.''
</P>
<P>
   The Potomac Raritan Magothy aquifer supplies 75 percent of the
state's drinking water. It runs underground in a swath that crosses
New Jersey from Middlesex and Monmouth counties at the northeast
through Mercer, Burlington, Camden, Gloucester and Salem counties.
The aquifer continues into Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Evenson compares it to a seven-layer cake. Some of the layers
are made of sand and gravel, which let water flow through, and
others are made of clay, which confine the water.
</P>
<P>
   Pumping out too much of the water in the aquifer can draw salt
water up into shallower wells or cause streams to dry up. The
Department of Environmental Protection is trying to ensure that the
additional development would not cause such problems, Evenson said.
</P>
<P>
   In its study, the U.S. Geological Survey is using computer
models to project what effect increased demand for water would have
on the aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The computer can look at the aquifer in three dimensions. It
divides it up into little boxes and there are calculations that
talk about how much water can be transferred from one box into the
next,'' Evenson said.
</P>
<P>
   They expect to give their results to the Department of
Environmental Protection next month, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the 22-square-mile farming community of Woolwich Township,
about 15 miles southwest of Philadelphia, plans approved in 1997
called for 4,500 homes, a school and a town center to be built in a
project called Weatherby. The development alone would house
thousands more than the entire township population of 2,700 today.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Environmental Protection in March rescinded
water permits for the first 500 homes. The state has since granted
some water permits, which are required before building permits can
be issued.
</P>
<P>
   Permits also have been withheld for housing developments in
Harrison and Logan townships in Gloucester County and an industrial
park in Pedricktown, Salem County.
</P>
<P>
   Woolwich Township Construction Code Official James Sabetta said
Monday that he can issue only about a dozen more building permits
before he reaches the limit of 256 imposed by the Department of
Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Wittenberg, director of environmental affairs at the New
Jersey Builders Association, wonders why the moratorium was
necessary in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The area in question is designated for growth in the proposed
state master plan, which is expected to be adopted later this year
by the State Planning Commission. The plan identifies places where
building should take place and others that should be left
undeveloped.
</P>
<P>
   ''Either the state plan is wrong and somebody should stand up
and say that, or DEP should get out of the way and let development
go where it says it should go,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Evenson, too, said that according to the state's water supply
master plan, which calculates anticipated water demand through
2040, the area in question was not expected to have a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't believe the demand for water was projected at the
level that applications for permits (have reached),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Department of Environmental Protection
did not return several calls requesting comment Monday. Robert
Oberthaler, director of the department's Bureau of Water
Allocation, told The Philadelphia Inquirer last week that the
department was inundated with requests for water permits from rural
areas where they never expected population growth.
</P>
<P>
   He said the new users could threaten the lower portion of the
Potomac Raritan Magothy aquifer.
</P>
<P>
   Wittenberg said builders already have lost a lot of time and
money because of the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   ''Builders carry this land, they pay taxes on this land, they
have financing on the land,'' she said. ''All these things come
into play.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://nj.usgs.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 1743 </TRAILER>
