<DOCNO> APW20000828.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heart Drug Proves Disappointing  </HEADLINE>
By EMMA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- A clot-blocking drug that doctors
thought would help stabilize people immediately after a near-heart
attack and reduce their chances of dying or having a heart attack
is a disappointment, new research shows.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, abciximab, which inhibits sticky blood cells from
clumping together, saves lives when heart patients undergo invasive
artery-widening treatments such as angioplasty by making such
operations safer and more effective.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been so impressive that scientists expected it
also would improve the outcome in patients who did not undergo
surgery. But it made no difference at all.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was a big shock,'' said Dr. Frans Van de Werf, chairman
of cardiology at Belgium's Catholic University, who was not
connected with the research. ''Nobody understands why.''
</P>
<P>
   The findings were presented Monday at a conference of the
European Society of Cardiology.
</P>
<P>
   In the international study of 7,800 heart patients who came to
hospitals with severe chest pain linked to a near-heart attack, all
the patients immediately got aspirin -- a mild clot preventer -- and
one of two version of the blood thinner heparin, which is a
standard treatment for that condition.
</P>
<P>
   Such patients have a high risk of having an actual heart attack
because, although their artery blockages have not completely shut
down blood flow, they hover on the verge of doing so, opening and
closing, then opening again.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the aspirin and blood thinner, half the patients
got an intravenous infusion of abciximab for 24 or 48 hours and
half got a fake drug.
</P>
<P>
   The study aimed to test whether adding abciximab reduced the
chances they would have a heart attack or die within the first
month.
</P>
<P>
   Eight percent of those who did not receive abciximab had a heart
attack or died within the month, compared with 8.2 percent of those
on the 24-hour infusion and 9.6 percent of those on the 48-hour
drip.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not an indication of benefit to these patients,'' said Dr.
Maarten Simoons, one of the study's leaders and a professor of
medicine at Erasmus University Hospital in Rotterdam, Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Also, about the same proportion in each group -- about 2 percent
-- needed to have their arteries unblocked during that time.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists had hoped the drug could spare patients surgery
or angioplasty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many of us were convinced that this would work. All the data
have pointed in the same direction,'' Simoons said.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible the study did not find a benefit of abciximab
because it was not large enough to show a difference or because
using the drug for a such a long time is not a good idea, Simoons
said. Abciximab is usually given for 12 hours before and during
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Farkouh, a professor at Mount Sinai School of
Medicine in New York, said the assumption it would help heart
patients who were not having an artery operation within hours was a
fair one. But he added that the results of the study were, in a
way, not altogether surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ''We knew all along that these drugs were best for patients
undergoing intervention,'' he said. ''That's where all the evidence
was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 1759 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
