<HEADLINE> An analysis of Lazio ad stressing his legislative work  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of the new Rick Lazio ad in which the
Republican
Senate candidate's campaign responds to claims made in ads by his
Democratic opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITLE: ''Positive.''
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Murphy Pintak Gautier Hudome Agency.
</P>
<P>
   AIRING: Statewide starting Monday.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: (Read by a male announcer) ''Compare: Congressman Rick
Lazio is running a positive campaign about his accomplishments for
New York. Hillary Clinton is running a negative campaign because
she's done nothing for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Her new ad contains five gross distortions in just 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Lazio has voted to support Medicare and for prescription
drugs. Look it up - it's all there in the Congressional Record.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton - you just can't trust her.''
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES: Lazio and Clinton appear at top of screen, with their
corresponding commercials running underneath them. Underneath the
Lazio commercial, a blue graphic says ''Positive,'' while Clinton's
appears in a red graphic ''Negative.''
</P>
<P>
   A graphic reading ''Five gross distortions in 30 seconds''
appears over the Clinton commercial, on the right of the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a Lazio graphic appears, with the words, ''Support
Medicare'' (HR 3075 and H Con. Res. 84-6/5/97) and ''For
Prescription Drugs'' (HR 4680-6/28/00) written underneath, and a
graphic of a Congressional Record's letterhead.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial ends with white letters on a black screen:
Hillary Clinton. You Just Can't Trust Her.
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: Lazio media guru Michael Murphy said the commercial is
intended to counter the Clinton campaign's advertising. ''It's time
to hit back and hit back hard,'' Murphy said in announcing ''a
large media buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad, like a number of commercials from both sides in the
campaign so far, relies on the viewer to dissect the votes Lazio
has taken during his eight years in Congress. In many cases, Lazio
has voted in favor of Republican versions of legislation, but the
Clinton campaign cites his votes against Democratic proposals.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON RESPONSE: ''The Lazio campaign has taken hypocrisy to a
new level - they are running a negative ad and calling it
''positive.'' Once again, Rick Lazio is trying to mislead New
Yorkers about his record - he says he's a moderate but was deputy
to (House Speaker Newt) Gingrich, voted to cut Medicare funding,
and said his tax plan cost $776 billion while the Daily News and
Newsday say it really costs well over $1 trillion. This ad should
come with a consumer warning: New Yorkers can't trust what Rick
Lazio says,'' said Clinton spokeswoman Cathie Levine.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Analysis by Frank Eltman, Associated Press Writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
