<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SUNY trustees approve New Covenant's revised charter  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The State University of New York Board of
Trustees Monday approved New Covenant Charter School's amended
charter, allowing it to open after Labor Day under a new management
company.
</P>
<P>
   The charter school in Albany was also immediately put on
probation and required to adhere to a remedial action plan to be
set by SUNY's Charter School Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The charter approval from SUNY trustees came about two weeks
after New Covenant submitted its revised charter, calling for the
switch from its former management company, Boston-based Advantage
Schools, Inc., to Edison Schools, Inc., headquartered in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bellafiore, executive director of the Charter School
Institute, said putting New Covenant on probation was the
''strongest sanction short of (charter) revocation.''
</P>
<P>
   The probation action was also necessary to ensure that the
school will open on Sept. 7 without final approval of the charter
amendment, Bellafiore said. The charter now goes to the state Board
of Regents, which can comment or make suggestions on the charter
but does not have veto power over the license.
</P>
<P>
   New Covenant, which opened as the largest of New York's first
three charter schools last fall, saw its first school year plagued
by academic, disciplinary and managerial problems. A promise in the
original charter to build a permanent facility by February this
year wasn't fulfilled and students are still housed in temporary
modular classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   These troubles were underscored in critical reports released by
the Charter School Institute and the state Board of Education this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many, if not most, charter schools have bumpy first years. New
Covenant's was bumpier, if not more than most,'' Bellafiore said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the remedial action plan, enrollment will be capped at 400
students, fewer than the original target of 424. The school will
not be allowed to fill any vacancies for as long as the school is
operating in its temporary classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also calls for mandatory training sessions for New
Covenant's Board of Trustees, submission of monthly financial
reports and mid-year and year-end formal reviews.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Charter School Institute will appoint a third
party to monitor the financing and construction of a new school
building. Edison has promised to build a $10 million facility to
house up to 800 students in grades kindergarten through eight. The
new building, which will include a community center, a swimming
pool and a gym, is expected to be completed by fall 2001, Edison
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Bellafiore said the remedial action plan will serve ''not as a
punishment, but as a tool for accountability,'' Bellafiore said.
Failure to comply with any part of the plan could mean immediate
revocation of New Covenant's charter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The school is taking the steps it needs to straighten itself
out,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Cox, co-chairman of SUNY's Committee on Charter Schools,
said the appointment of Eleanor Bartlett, a former Regent, as New
Covenant's new director gave him ''great confidence in this school
going forward and making this a success.''
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett, who has previously served as assistant superintendent
in the Albany City School District, said she was ''excited and a
little afraid'' with the task ahead of her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know we've had problems, but we're moving forward. If we go
with the children, we can't go wrong,'' Bartlett said. ''I know we
can turn this school around ... I'm staking my career on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charter schools are taxpayer-funded but operate with an
independent charter that spells out the school's mission. They are
offered as alternatives to parents dissatisfied with traditional
public school education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 1813 </TRAILER>
