<HEADLINE> Turkey Drops Warrant vs. Preacher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- A Turkish court on Monday withdrew an
arrest warrant for an Islamic preacher prosecutors say leads a
group trying to overthrow Turkey's secular regime.
</P>
<P>
   Fethullah Gulen, who is believed to live in the United States,
is now free to return to Turkey if he wishes to. However, his
lawyer, Orhan Erdemli, said he would not come back because he is in
poor health.
</P>
<P>
   Gulen, 62, reportedly left Turkey last year for the United
States to seek medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Erdemli said prosecutors will continue to investigate charges
that Gulen was leading a criminal group and inciting religious
hatred. Gulen faces a maximum 15-year prison sentence if found
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Secularism is rigorously enforced in Turkey and Turkey's
government, backed by the powerful military, has launched a
crackdown against political Islam.
</P>
<P>
   The court ruled Monday that there were no grounds for the arrest
warrant while the investigation was ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   Gulen has a large following among Turks, who regard him as a
moderate Islamic figure who preaches tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Turkish television stations aired a videotape in
which Gulen appeared to be urging his followers to keep a low
profile before attempting an uprising. It was not clear how the
tape was released to television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Gulen runs scores of religious schools in Turkey and Central
Asia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
