<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 60; Nasdaq Up 28  </HEADLINE>
By DUNSTAN PRIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved higher Monday, a possible sign that
investors are more confident about the future direction of stock
prices following several days of indecision.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 60.21 at 11,252.84,
after rising more than 120 points earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also advanced.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index gained 27.91 to 4,070.59 and is now
up slightly for the year, marking the first time the technology
heavy index has been in positive territory since early spring. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 7.64 to 1,514.09.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks had fluctuated last week, while mostly moving higher, as
investors began to recognize that interest rate hikes no longer
seem to be a factor in trading.
</P>
<P>
   ''Investors have been extremely lackadaisical in the past few
sessions,'' said Don Hays, president of Hays Advisory Group in
Nashville, Tenn. But, he said, ''people seem comfortable that there
won't be any more interest rate hikes.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial stocks were up across the board Monday on the belief
that stable interest rates will encourage borrowing and improve the
lucrative business of underwriting stocks and bonds. J.P. Morgan
gained $1.125 to $145.125, and Citigroup rose $1.92 to $58.875.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the recent move upward has lacked conviction, in part,
because energy prices remain high and labor markets tight -- both
factors that could contribute to a rise in inflation. In addition,
companies in several industrial sectors have warned that profits
may be down in the second half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   These dynamics could pose obstacles as the markets try to
reclaim their highs of early spring.
</P>
<P>
   Hays noted that trading volume on Friday was at its lowest level
of the year and remained low Monday. Moreover, he noted that stocks
were being propelled on Monday on the strength of a handful of
stocks in a small number of sectors, something known as a lack of
breadth in the market.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the market has been sector-driven for several weeks,
meaning that investors are essentially rotating money in and out of
industries that are rising or falling based on short-term trading
trends.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was led on Monday by widely held stocks such as IBM, up
$1.563 to $130.563, and EMC Corp., up $4 to $95.50.
</P>
<P>
   The same pattern held true on the Nasdaq, where well known
technology stocks led the way. Intel rose 93.75 cents to $73.875,
Cisco Systems gained 56.25 cents to $66.06, and Dell Computer was
up 87.50 cents at $39.50.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks, which have been out of favor since the spring,
moved back into the spotlight, helping to lift the Nasdaq. Search
engine company Lycos rose $1.625 to $67.438.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo!, however, a star last week, was hit hard after analysts
warned that the Internet portal's revenues may fall as Internet
advertising slows later in the year. Yahoo!'s shares fell $12.188
to $122.063.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners 5-to-4 on the New York
Stock Exchange, where composite volume came to 908.12 million
shares, up from Friday's pace of 844.06 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.37 at 526.48.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.60 percent.
Germany's DAX index was up 0.44 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was up
0.10 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 0.30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
