<HEADLINE> Two killed when motorcycle, emergency vehicle, collide in Brooklyn  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A father and son were killed when their
motorcycle collided with an emergency vehicle in Brooklyn, and
police were investigating whether the vehicle was properly licensed
to operate as an ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Curtis, 37, and his 13-year-old son, Alberto Jr., both
of Brooklyn, were traveling south on Ocean Parkway around 9:20 p.m.
Sunday, when they passed through a green traffic light at Avenue L
and collided with a 1988 Ford Station Wagon that has ambulance
plates, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The station wagon, registered to the Hatzoloh Ambulance Corp., a
private company that serves Jewish residents, had its lights and
sirens on. The driver, Shamai Goldstein, 31, was responding to a
call of a 75-year-old woman with chest pains, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The motorcycle hit the left front portion of the station wagon,
ejecting both riders. Although both wore helmets, they sustained
multiple injuries and were pronounced dead a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis has a valid motorcycle driver's license registered in
Iowa, but not in New York, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis' 31-year-old nephew and 14-year-old niece - who were on
another motorcycle - witnessed the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Goldstein was treated for minor injuries at
Maimonides Hospital and released.
</P>
<P>
   Police were still investigating Monday. One aspect they are
looking into is whether the station wagon was properly licensed to
operate as an ambulance.
</P>
</TEXT>
