<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safir rebuked, but not charged, in Oscar trip  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The city's Conflict of Interest Board publicly
rebuked Howard Safir on Monday for taking an all-expenses paid trip
with a Revlon executive to the Academy Awards, but said the former
police commissioner did not violate any city laws - although Revlon
was doing business with the NYPD through a corporate affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Safir's trip to Hollywood drew criticism because at the time,
daily protests were being held in front of police headquarters that
called for justice for Amadou Diallo, fatally shot by four police
officers in February 1999 in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The five-member board completed the report on Aug. 16, but could
not publicly release it without holding a full hearing on the
matter, or unless Safir agreed to the public disclosure. Joan
Salzman, the board's deputy executive director and chief of
enforcement, said Safir agreed to the disclosure Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But in a telephone interview from his Manhattan apartment, Safir
said he signed the disclosure on Aug. 18, his last day as
commissioner, then gave the papers to the Corporation Counsel.
Daniel Connolly, a Corporation Counsel lawyer, said he was unsure
when the board received Safir's disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Safir denied doing anything wrong, although he is only the
second public official to be rebuked by the board. A Board of
Education spokesman was publicly rebuked in 1996 for working as a
consultant to a private education group that held city contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm vindicated. If I wasn't vindicated, they would have
charged me with something,'' Safir said. ''I don't accept their
rebuke.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir said he has reimbursed Revlon President and Chief
Executive Officer George Fellows for the trip he took from March
20-22, 1999. Salzman confirmed that Safir had repaid Fellows with a
check drawn on his personal account for $7,079.21, dated Jan. 22,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Safir and his wife, Carol, flew to Los Angeles on a private jet
leased by Revlon, stayed in the Peninsula Beverly Hills Hotel, and
were given tickets to the Oscars - all free of charge. Safir
returned to New York City on March 22 by commercial airline at his
own expense, while his wife returned on the private jet.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Safir's spokeswoman, Marilyn Mode, had said he might not
attend a City Council committee hearing on the Street Crime Unit on
March 22 because of an undisclosed ''scheduling conflict.'' But
under pressure, Safir returned in time for the meeting. The
officers who shot Diallo had been assigned to the Street Crime
Unit.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has defended Safir's trip. Safir has said
repeatedly he did not think he broke any rules because Revlon does
not do business with the city and he was invited on the trip
because Fellows is a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Under city rules, a public servant cannot accept a gift worth
$50 or more from any person or business that the public servant
knows is or intends to become engaged in business with the city.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling, the board, which is appointed by the mayor and
confirmed by the City Council, said Safir should have found out
first whether Revlon was doing any business with the police
department. Through a corporate affiliate, Revlon uses the NYPD's
''paid detail program,'' paying the department $6,000 over the last
two years for uniformed officers for private security.
</P>
<P>
   Salzman said this was the first time the board had to define the
context of the city's gift rules. She added that even if Safir had
tried to find out if Revlon was doing business with Revlon, it
would have been difficult for him to find such records because all
business dealings were kept manually and stored in the NYPD's paid
detail office.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a sense that it was unfair to charge him, since the
board has never addressed what duty of inquiry a public official
has when offered a high-level gift,'' Salzman said. ''Where the
board faulted him is where he failed to inquire at all - he just
accepted the gift, on the erroneous theory that the donor was a
close, personal friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachel Leon, executive director of Common Cause/New York, said
the board's ruling should put other public officials on notice
about accepting gifts. The group has been lobbying for the state
Legislature to prohibit public officials from accepting any gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cops can't take a cup of coffee from anyone, and the law
should be simple and clear like that, meaning no gifts,'' Leon
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 1837 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecutor gets two more months to evaluate evidence  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Prosecutors now have two more months to
investigate claims by new eyewitnesses and to assess how that
evidence affects their criminal case against two state troopers who
fired on a van after a traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   The judge overseeing the case agreed to the state's request for
a delay and postponed his scheduled decision on defense motions to
dismiss the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need more time to continue our investigation and also to
really evaluate what our response is going to be,'' Special Deputy
Attorney General James J. Gerrow said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's court-ordered deadline was Thursday, a date set
after Gerrow's public disclosure Aug. 1 that two new eyewitnesses
had come forward. In his letter to the judge, Gerrow said the
state's ''efforts to resolve these issues'' continue and remain
''as yet, unresolved''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gerrow declined to detail what the state would do
between now and the newest deadline of Oct. 26. He also would not
detail how the new evidence changes the state's case against
troopers John Hogan and James Kenna.
</P>
<P>
   ''As all criminal cases are built on building blocks of
evidence, as some change, that change affects the other building
blocks. We really need time to evaluate that,'' Gerrow said.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan and Kenna fired 11 shots into the van, wounding three
passengers in April 1998. They stopped the van with four minority
men inside because they believed the driver had been speeding. Both
troopers have repeatedly claimed they fired in self-defense, saying
they feared the driver of the van was attempting to run them over.
</P>
<P>
   Public outcry after the shooting led to widespread allegations
of racial profiling by state troopers and a severely critical
report by the New Jersey attorney general's office detailing the
practice.
</P>
<P>
   An indictment came after nearly two years of investigation by
the state, including a complete re-enactment of the shooting that
closed part of the turnpike for a time.
</P>
<P>
   A pending motion asks state Superior Court Judge Andrew J.
Smithson to dismiss the indictment due to defense claims that
biased prosecutors led a grand jury to indict the troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Smithson now says that decision will come during a hearing
scheduled for Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers still do not know exactly what the two new
witnesses told the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''It appears to be significant enough,'' defense attorney Jack
Arsenault said.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenault, who represents Kenna, said he initially rejected
Gerrow's attempt to delay the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ''These two new witnesses really seem to corroborate more of
what the troopers said than what they (prosecutors) initially
thought. It's given them much more of a perspective on the case,''
Arsenault said.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenault said it is still unclear if the witnesses version of
the events clear one or both of the troopers. Prosecutors must now
re-examine all the evidence, everything from statements taken that
night to reports from forensic experts, Arsenault said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's enough here that they really have to evaluate their
entire case,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
