<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman signs first in a five-bill, $61 million package to preserve land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman Monday signed the
first of five bills slated to become law this week to pump $61
million into land preservation for parks and wildlife refuges.
</P>
<P>
   ''With the bills I sign this week, we will move tens of
thousands of acres closer to that amount, and that much closer to
our ultimate goal of 1 million this decade,'' Whitman said. ''We
will also build momentum for the kinds of partnerships between
public, private and nonprofit leaders that will help us reach our
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The package of bills expected to be approved this week follow
two bills she signed Aug. 9 to preserve farmland.
</P>
<P>
   A bill to provide $6.6 million to 15 nonprofit groups was signed
Monday at ceremonies on a wild parcel in Lawrence Township which is
targeted for preservation by the Delaware &AMP; Raritan Greenway. The
property is part of a creek watershed affecting both the Stony
Brook and D&AMP;R Canal waterways, where extensive preservation has
taken place.
</P>
<P>
   The unique aspect of the bill is direct state funding to
nonprofit groups that have proposals to buy land, usually with a
mix of funding sources. In the past, such groups had to acquire
land on their own and seek state or federal funds afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Among the grants is $500,000 for the Tewksbury Land Trust to
preserve land in the governor's hometown, and another $500,000 to a
similar outfit for save land in the neighboring town of
Peapack-Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman is scheduled Tuesday to sign a $14 million spending bill
at a farm in Union Township in Hunterdon County, some of it to
expand the land in county and state parks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
