<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Department of Interior rejects town leaders' allegations  </HEADLINE>
jffonho
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH STONINGTON, Conn. (AP) - The Department of Interior will
not investigate claims made by three Connecticut towns that the top
official at the Bureau of Indian Affairs has a conflict of interest
in the federal recognition case of two Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   The towns of North Stonington, Ledyard and Preston had asked
that Bureau of Indian Affairs director Kevin Gover be removed from
a decision on whether to grant federal recognition to the Paucatuck
Eastern Pequot and Eastern Pequot tribes. They claim Gover has a
conflict because he once served as an attorney for the Golden Hill
Paugusetts, another Connecticut tribe seeking recognition.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal Office of Inspector General ruled Monday that
the towns have failed to show how Gover's former position resulted
in a conflict. The office also said that by law, the BIA director
must be involved in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Moreover, it is premature to consider whether (Gover) acted
improperly in making the federal acknowledgment determination for
the tribe because the Department has not issued a final decision,''
Deputy Inspector General Mary Kendall Adler wrote in an Aug. 23
letter to James Cunha, chief of the Paucatuck Eastern Pequot Indian
Tribal Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Cunha said the BIA's decision ''backs up what we have been
saying about the town leaders and their attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They are only interested in trying to create delay, discord
and confusion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Richard Blumenthal, who has also
requested that Gover step aside, said the Department of Interior
has not responded to his, more detailed claim.
</P>
<P>
   ''This letter is not necessarily the final word on whether there
is a conflict of interest and what should be done about that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Blumenthal said the point may be moot. Gover has said he
will step down at the end of the Clinton administration. A final
decision on whether to recognize the tribes is not expected until
after a new BIA official takes office.
</P>
<P>
   In a preliminary ruling in March, the BIA said the tribes meet
the criteria for federal recognition, including maintaining a
continuous historical government-to-government relationship with
the state since colonial times.
</P>
<P>
   But Preston First Selectman Robert Congdon said the towns still
have ''several remedies'' available to push for an investigation -
including seeking Congressional support or relief through the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We built a record throughout this process that supports the
claims that we raise on this issue,'' Congdon said Monday. ''The
BIA has done everything that can to stall and delay the towns'
efforts to receive the full and complete record.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
