<HEADLINE> Sierra Club airing ads in 12 congressional races  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - The Sierra Club is returning to the airwaves
in seven states with television and radio ads praising a few
Republicans and many more Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The ads, many of which spotlight local environmental issues, are
part of an $8 million campaign to boost candidates that support the
club's environmental agenda and skewer those who don't.
</P>
<P>
   One radio ad praises a Republican and a Democrat - each of whom
represent districts served by stations in the Quad Cities, Iowa,
area. Listeners are asked to thank Reps. Jim Leach, R-Iowa, and
Lane Evans, D-Ill., for supporting higher standards on arsenic in
drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The ad buy, which is for about two weeks, is costing the Sierra
Club more than $200,000, said Dan Weiss, the group's political
director.
</P>
<P>
   Positive TV ads will air about Democratic Reps. Mark Udall of
Colorado, Joseph Hoeffel of Pennsylvania and Brian Baird of
Washington state. Radio ads will support Republican Sens. Jim
Jeffords of Vermont and William Roth of Delaware, along with
Democratic Reps. Rush Holt of New Jersey and Jay Inslee and Adam
Smith, both of Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Critical ads are airing against two Republicans, Sen. Slade
Gorton of Washington state and former Virginia Gov. George Allen, a
Senate hopeful. Television ads are airing in both races, with radio
spots also planned for Gorton.
</P>
</TEXT>
