<HEADLINE> Record Fine for Lockheed Proposed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAK RIDGE, Tenn. (AP) -- The Department of Energy on Monday
proposed a record $1 million fine against one of its top
contractors stemming from a chemical explosion and other safety
violations at the Y-12 nuclear weapons plant.
</P>
<P>
   The fine against Lockheed Martin Energy Systems, which runs the
weapons plant, would be the largest under the department's nuclear
safety enhancement program begun in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   DOE program administrator John Gordon called it ''an important
tool that we can use to assure that our contractors are fully
accountable for safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin was cited for a Dec. 8 chemical explosion that
injured 11 workers. The contractor also was sanctioned for improper
handling of nuclear materials and other safety violations that led
to a department-ordered ''stand down'' of the plant on Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department noted that some problems were identified
by the Defense Nuclear Facility Safety Board as early as 1994, but
that penalties were deferred then because of the contractor's
promises to make improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging some improvements have been made recently, the
department said Lockheed Martin has until Sept. 23 to explain why
it shouldn't be fined now.
</P>
<P>
   ''We recognized these issues, reported them to the Department of
Energy and identified actions to correct them,'' said Bob Van Hook,
Lockheed Martin Energy Systems president.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going forward and are fully committed to the safe,
secure and reliable operation of the Y-12 plant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Department of Energy violation notice:
http://www.eh.doe.gov/enforce
</P>
</TEXT>
