<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PETA, Giuliani consider suits over 'Got prostate cancer?' ads  </HEADLINE>
By JR ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   Got lawsuit?
</P>
<P>
   People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals threatened Monday to
sue a Wisconsin advertising company that pulled down its billboards
spoofing the ''Got milk?'' campaign with an ad featuring the
likeness of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to suggest a link
between dairy products and prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has the disease, shot back Monday that he's
considering a lawsuit of his own against PETA for the ad that
pictures him with a milk mustache and ''Got prostate cancer?''
emblazoned across the billboard.
</P>
<P>
   PETA spokesman Bruce Friedrich said the group's lawyer gave
French Advertising Inc. until Tuesday to respond to its demand to
put the billboards back up in two Wisconsin cities. Otherwise, PETA
planned to sue to force the company to honor its contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have a very legal right to use the graphic that we're
using,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Fond du Lac, Wis., company sent PETA a fax Friday saying it
would remove the billboards in Appleton and Oshkosh because the
group had not obtained Giuliani's permission to use his likeness in
designing the ads.
</P>
<P>
   A third board planned for Fond du Lac never went up. Another
outside Lancaster, Pa., was still up Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''My hunch is they got pressure and caved,'' Friedrich said.
</P>
<P>
   French Advertising did not return a message The Associated Press
left Monday seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he was still thinking about suing PETA for using
his likeness in the ad campaign. He said the ad gives the
impression that he supports PETA, which he doesn't, and that
there's a link between dairy products and prostate cancer, which is
disputed.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard School of Public Health study in April raised the
possibility that consuming dairy products may increase the risk of
prostate cancer. But the study also said the issue was far from
settled and recommended further study of calcium's effects on
health.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're not doing it because they care about cancer. This
isn't the American Cancer Association,'' Giuliani said. ''They're
worried about cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Friedrich said PETA plans to put up the ''Got prostate
cancer?'' billboards in others states. The ad campaign spoofs the
''Got milk?'' ads, which show famous people with milk mustaches.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time an ad featuring Giuliani was the
subject of a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   New York magazine sued the Metropolitan Transportation Authority
after it removed the publication's ads from buses because they
offended Giuliani. The ad featured the magazine's logo and read,
''Possibly the only good thing in New York Rudy hasn't taken credit
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani asked the MTA to remove the ads. The agency did, citing
a state law barring the commercial use of any living person's name
without consent.
</P>
<P>
   A federal trial judge called the ad a ''hybrid of commercial
speech and political satire,'' and ruled that it was entitled to
constitutional protection. The 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ruled against MTA and the U.S. Supreme Court denied its appeal
without comment in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   MTA put the ads back up after the lower court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   PETA: http://www.peta-online.org/
</P>
<P>
   International Dairy Foods Association: http://www.idfa.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 1938 </TRAILER>
