<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mets Option McEwing, Call Reliever  </HEADLINE>
By JOSH DUBOW
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Concerned about the health of reliever John
Franco, the New York Mets purchased the contract of right-handed
reliever Jerrod Riggan from Double-A Binghamton on Monday and
optioned utilityman Joe McEwing to Triple-A Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Franco hasn't pitched since last Tuesday because of a strained
pectoral muscle in his left shoulder and Mets manager Bobby
Valentine didn't want his already-stretched bullpen to operate a
pitcher short.
</P>
<P>
   ''With Franco day to day and the fact that (Armando) Benitez has
pitched four of five days and Rick White has pitched so much, Bobby
wanted another pitcher,'' general manager Steve Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Franco, 39, has given up just one unearned run in his last 19
2-3 innings dating to June 24. He could be back as early as
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's getting better,'' Franco said. ''But we have a pretty
good cushion in the wild card race, so I don't want to push it.
</P>
<P>
   Riggan, 26, was 2-0 with 27 saves and a 1.16 ERA at Binghamton.
He wasn't the Mets' first choice, but Triple-A reliever Eric
Cammack got stuck in Norfolk, Va., because of bad weather.
Eventually the Mets called Riggan, who drove down from Binghamton,
N.Y., and arrived just before the game against Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Cammack could replace Riggan on Tuesday or be called up when
rosters expand Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a tough break for him,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   McEwing is hitting .227 with two homers and 18 RBIs. He must
stay at Norfolk until the end of the Triple-A season Sept. 4 unless
a player on the Mets' 25-man roster gets injured.
</P>
<P>
   He can be eligible for the postseason roster -- even though he
will be in the minors on Aug. 31 -- because shortstop Rey Ordonez is
on the 60-day disabled list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
