<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Votes Are Being Counted in Lebanon  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Former Prime Minister Rafik Hariri made a
strong showing in the first round of parliamentary elections, with
allied candidates taking the majority of the 63 contested seats in
northern and central Lebanon, according to official results Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A tally of winners and losers from Sunday's vote in central and
northern Lebanon showed candidates backed by Hariri or tilting
toward him winning 34 out of the 63 seats, Interior Minister Michel
Murr announced.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri, a billionaire businessman who made his fortune in
construction in Saudi Arabia, is waging an undeclared battle for
the premiership against Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
   Elections for the remaining 65 seats in the 128-member
legislature will be held next Sunday in the capital Beirut, where
Hoss and Hariri are running for different seats. For the first time
in three decades, balloting will include the border zone vacated by
Israel in May.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a victory for democracy in Lebanon and a proof that
the system is working,'' Hariri said of the results.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's upset could have an effect on who becomes the next
prime minister. However, little was expected to change in Lebanon's
political landscape since both men are close to Syria, which has
30,000 troops in Lebanon and dominates this country militarily and
politically.
</P>
<P>
   Although the campaign was short on issues, the results reflected
public dissatisfaction with the government's policies.
</P>
<P>
   The government came under fire from opponents for its handling
of an economy in recession and for what the opposition says was the
increasing influence of the security services in the running of the
country. Opposition candidates have charged that the government's
security agencies have tried to influence the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Druse leader Walid Jumblatt, a legislator and a harsh government
critic, and his supporters swept 16 of the 35 seats in the Mount
Lebanon province. The outspoken Jumblatt, one of the rare voices to
publicly criticize the increasing role of the state's security
services in political life, said the results send a strong message
to the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri launched a multibillion-dollar program to rebuild Lebanon
from the devastation of the civil war during his 1992-1998 tenure.
He has been accused by the Hoss government of shackling Lebanon
with more than $20 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Hariri may not be able to count for long on pre-election
alliances that have pulled together candidates from different
factions.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong showing for candidates he backed gave a boost to
his comeback bid for the premiership. The former prime minister
stepped down in November 1998 after a power struggle with President
Emile Lahoud. Under Lebanon's parliamentary system, the president
selects the prime minister after polling legislators on their
choice.
</P>
<P>
   Among the new young faces to win parliamentary seats in Mount
Lebanon are Lahoud's 25-year-old son, Emile Jr., and Pierre
Gemayel, the 29-year-old son of former President Amin Gemayel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2000 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New game is tied to state-required exams  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Meeting New York's new learning
requirements doesn't have to mean all work and no play for
students. Two Niagara County entrepreneurs have developed a board
game designed to help players prepare for the state-required exams.
</P>
<P>
   Creators Bob Hartz and Jeff Dinse of Wilson are busy shopping
''Master Guru'' around to school districts just in time for the
start of the new school year.
</P>
<P>
   So far they've found buyers in dozens of western New York
districts, including Hamburg, Williamsville, Niagara Falls and
Sweet Home.
</P>
<P>
   Dinse, a seventh-grade social studies teacher at Kenmore Middle
School, got the idea from a technique he used in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've used a Trivial Pursuit-like game to quiz my kids on the
social studies curriculum and it hit me that something like it
could be used for all the subjects covered by the state tests,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartz, a childhood friend and University of Rochester baseball
coach, agreed. The two formed a company called Harbor Town Games
and, with input from several fellow educators, came up with a game
for young students covering materials from the social studies,
math, science and English portions of the state tests.
</P>
<P>
   ''We decided to start with a third-grade-level game, so we can
catch kids who are having their first introduction to the subject
matter they'll be tested on as fourth-graders,'' Dinse said.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Swanson, a Kenmore Middle School art teacher, was called
in to help with graphic elements of the game board, cards and
packaging.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a challenging game where players move through
three increasingly difficult levels of play to become Master Gurus.
To advance, players must answer questions from printed cards, each
of which has the correct answer and an explanation on the back.
</P>
<P>
   ''With math and science questions, it's really important to show
the steps or formula used to reach the answer,'' Dinse said. ''We
also think it will be very helpful to parents, who might need to
see an explanation themselves, so they can be a resource to their
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   While the current version of the game is geared for New York
third- and fourth-graders, versions for other grade levels are in
the works and the partners eventually would like to create editions
for students nationwide, noting that nearly every state has adopted
learning standards in recent years to boost academic proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's down the road a ways,'' Dinse said. ''Right now, our
big step was to move the business out of my garage into 3,600
square feet of rented space.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Harbor Town Games: http://www.mastergurugames.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 2004 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman-Cline Leaving the Shock  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Nancy Lieberman-Cline, the only coach and general
manager the Detroit Shock have ever had, won't be back with the
team next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Shock said Monday it is not renewing the Hall of Famer's
contract. No replacement was named.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am extremely appreciative of the opportunity that Detroit
game me to be involved with the Shock and the WNBA,''
Lieberman-Cline said in a statement. ''I enjoyed my three years in
Detroit, and I wish the players and franchise well in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   She led the Shock to a 46-48 record.
</P>
<P>
   The team finished over .500 in its inaugural 1998 season, and
made the playoffs in 1999. But the Shock went 4-8 down the stretch
this year to miss the playoffs by a game.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance dropped each season.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nancy helped establish women's professional basketball in the
state of Michigan,'' team president Tom Wilson said. ''We will now
begin the search for a new head coach and look forward to a
successful 2001 WNBA season.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman-Cline, nicknamed ''Lady Magic,'' was enshrined in the
Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   She led Old Dominion to two national championships, became the
youngest basketball player to win an Olympic medal at 18 -- a silver
in the 1976 Montreal Games -- and led the Dallas Diamonds of the
Women's Basketball League to the 1981 championship.
</P>
<P>
   She was the first woman to play in a men's professional league,
with the USBL's Springfield Fame and Long Island Knights, and
played for the Phoenix Mercury in the WNBA's inaugural season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2013 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Seeks Turkey Defense Ties  </HEADLINE>
By SELCAN HACAOGLU
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak lobbied
in Turkey on Monday for defense contracts amid reports that Turkey
was scaling back ties with Israeli firms.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials are apparently disappointed that Turkish firms
recently lost a major contract in Israel and were also angry that
an Israeli minister called for teaching the massacre of Armenians
along with the Holocaust in Israeli schools. Turkey insists that it
did not commit genocide against the Armenians during World War I
and regards any such allegations as anti-Turkish.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our defense industry would like to have more projects in
Turkey,'' Barak told reporters after meeting with Turkish Prime
Minister Bulent Ecevit. ''But we understand the rules of free
competition and Turkish authorities have to decide what is the best
thing for Turkey to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey expects to spend some $150 billion during the next 25
years to upgrade its armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli firms are already working to modernize Turkish F-4
Phantom jet fighters and are competing with Russia for a $4 billion
deal to produce 145 attack helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   But there are reports that Turkish officials have told Israel
that it is no longer in the running for contracts to build a spy
satellite, upgrade Turkish M-60 tanks and supply Turkey with radar
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Those reports came after Turkey reportedly lost out in the
bidding to repair the Israeli port of Ashdod.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey's private NTV television said Israel promised to award
construction work to Turkish companies in return for military
deals.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Ecevit also discussed Israel-Palestinian peace talks,
which stalled over the question of control of the city of
Jerusalem. Turkey has offered to act as a mediator. Barak returned
to Israel late Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2013 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Religious Leaders Gather  </HEADLINE>
By JULIA LIEBLICH
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Songs, cries and calls for prayer opened
the Millennium World Peace Summit of religious leaders at the
United Nations Monday, a gathering as much about private talks
between adversaries as formal resolutions passed in public.
</P>
<P>
   Participants say they hope the summit, which runs through
Thursday, will result in a declaration on peace, poverty and the
environment, as well as the formation of a council of religious
leaders to advise the United Nations on preventing and settling
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting of more than 1,000 leaders drew controversy
before it even began when participants learned last month that
conference organizers did not invite the Dalai Lama to the first
two days of the event for fear of offending China. China accuses
the Tibetan Buddhist leader and Nobel Peace Prize winner ''creating
turmoil'' in Tibet, from where he fled in 1959 after an abortive
uprising against China's occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Dissent on that issue aside, participants said they were
grateful for the event, considering the number of global conflicts
with strong religious components. Sessions were planned on the role
of religion in conflict resolution, with specific workshops on the
Balkans, Russia and Central Asia, Africa, and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   ''This afternoon, this General Assembly hall has become a
sanctuary,'' Bawa Jain, the summit general secretary, told an
audience in gilded robes and woven tunics, pointed caps and long
white veils.
</P>
<P>
   Some noted that the real work happens away from the podium
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you have a meeting between people who are officially
enemies who find they like each other,'' said Israeli Rabbi Adin
Steinsaltz, a leading Talmudic scholar. ''That makes more of a
difference than resolutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Eritrean Bishop Zekarias Yohannes said he plans to meet with
Ethiopian leaders. The two Horn of Africa neighbors recently signed
a cease-fire in a bitter border war.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Chief Rabbi Israel Meir Lau said he hopes to talk with
Muslim sheiks during the conference. ''Here we are not in a hostile
neighborhood,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Abdoulaye Dieye of Senegal said he had mixed feelings as
he entered the United Nations for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm full of hope, but I have fears,'' he said. ''The summit is
a very good thing for humanity if we manage it properly. There
shouldn't be too much politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet politics intruded on the issue of the Dalai Lama. During the
summit's opening session, a group of about 150 Tibetan monks,
exiles and activists protested in the plaza across from U.N.
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ''To not invite him is totally incongruous with what we're
trying to do here,'' said Yangdon Tsering, a Tibetan exile who
lives in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers invited the Dalai Lama only to the last two days of
the conference -- being held at a New York hotel. He declined.
</P>
<P>
   Bawa Jain, the chief summit organizer, said an eight-person
delegation of Tibetan Buddhist leaders had been sent by the Dalai
Lama, and that two of them would be speaking in the General
Assembly hall.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I don't want it to get into anything political,'' said
Jain, a member of the Jain faith from New Jersey by way of India.
''I've made that clear to them.''
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations did not sponsor the event nor issue
invitations. An interfaith coalition organized the program and
picked the participants. The only delegations chosen by their
government were China's and Vietnam's.
</P>
<P>
   Among the leaders on the program were Cardinal Francis Arinze,
president of the Vatican's Pontifical Council for Interreligious
Dialogue; Cambodian Buddhist leader Samdech Preah Maha Ghosananda;
the Grand Mufti of Bosnia, Mustafa Ceric and the Rev. Jesse
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders who declined to come include Ecumenical Patriarch
Bartholomew I, who sent a videotaped message, and Jerusalem Mufti
Ikrema Sabri, who has refused to meet with Rabbi Lau.
</P>
<P>
   The summit has received funding from Ted Turner's U.N.
Foundation, Better World Fund and others. Turner, who once said
that Christianity was ''for losers,'' will give the keynote
address.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2013 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Option Mike Kinkade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles optioned infielder Mike
Kinkade to Triple-A Rochester and returned outfielder Eugene
Kingsale to the minor league club Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkade, 28, was selected to the U.S. Olympic baseball team last
week. He is on his way to San Diego for a workout this week before
heading to Sydney, Australia, for next month's Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkade came to the Orioles in the June 28 trade that sent Mike
Bordick to the New York Mets. He went 3-for-7 in three games with
the Orioles, including a double to deliver the go-ahead run in
Sunday's 3-2 win over Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsale was placed on the 15-day disabled list March 29 with a
torn right quadriceps muscle and was placed on the 60-day DL on May
12. He hit a combined .385, going 20-for-52 with two home runs and
12 RBI in a 14-game rehab stint at Gulf Coast, Frederick and Bowie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
