<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Producer To Pay Sarah McLachlan's Court Costs
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- A music producer who
unsuccessfully sued singer Sarah McLachlan for copyright
infringement will have to pay the pop star more than $250,000 in
court costs.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Neudorf ''made serious allegations of copyright
infringement against'' the Grammy and Juno-awarding winning singer,
her label and managers, British Columbia Supreme Court Justice
Bruce Cohen said in his written ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Neudorf, a former drummer with the band 54-40, fail
to prove those allegations, but he also turned down a settlement
offer and forced a 39-day British Columbia Supreme Court trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the end of the day, based largely on the plaintiff's own
testimony, I held that the plaintiff had failed to prove'' his
claims, Cohen said in his ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Neudorf sued McLachlan -- the mastermind behind the wildly
successful Lilith Fair concert tour -- for cash and credit for work
on four songs on her 1998 debut album Touch.
---
Former Grand Chief Weighing Options
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Phil Fontaine, once Canada's most powerful
aboriginal leader, denies rumors he's on the verge of announcing
Liberal political ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   The former head of the Assembly of First Nations, defeated last
month in an upset victory by former Quebec Cree Grand Chief Matthew
Coon Come, says he's still weighing options.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't made any commitments'' on whether that includes
seeking a Liberal nomination for the next federal election,
Fontaine said in an interview Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you end up as a member of Parliament you represent not just
aboriginal issues. You represent the interests of all your
constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be careful about being seen as a single-issue or
special-interest representative,'' Fontaine said.
</P>
<P>
   He was responding to rumors that he'd announce during this
week's Liberal caucus meeting in Winnipeg plans to seek a
nomination in a Manitoba riding.
</P>
<P>
   ''There have been some discussions,'' Fontaine said from
Winnipeg. ''I've talked to people, people have talked to me, and
we've looked at the different possibilities. But there have been no
commitments made on either side.''
---
</P>
<P>
   Teen-ager Charged in Shooting Appears at Transfer Hearing
</P>
<P>
   LETHBRIDGE, Alberta (AP) -- A teen charged with gunning down a
fellow high school student listened calmly to the evidence in court
Monday while his mother sat nearby squeezing and clasping her
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be such a relief when this is over,'' the mother of
the 16-year-old boy said during a court break.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's been so hard for so many people. I just feel so bad for
those children.''
</P>
<P>
   The children are those involved in the shootings at the W. R.
Myers high school in Taber, Alberta, in April 1999. Jason Lang, 17,
was fatally shot and another student wounded in the school hallway.
A third student was also shot at but not hit.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of teen-agers came to youth court Monday to hear
details of that fateful, dark day at the southern Alberta school.
It was the beginning of a two-week hearing to determine whether the
accused will have his case moved to adult court.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged with one count of first-degree murder and two of
attempted murder.
</P>
<P>
   In youth court, he would face a maximum sentence of six years in
prison and four years community supervision. In adult court, the
maximum sentence for a 14-year-old young offender convicted of
first-degree murder is life in prison with no chance of parole for
five to seven years.
</P>
</TEXT>
