<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Chief Supports Grass-Roots Groups  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged
grass-roots groups from over 60 countries Monday to work with the
United Nations and its member governments to help make
globalization benefit the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
   Annan told more than 1,800 activists attending the annual U.N.
summit of non-governmental organizations that their misgivings
about the global economy -- which have resulted in protests at world
trade talks and other global gatherings -- were understandable.
</P>
<P>
   But he said activists should be part of the solution and not
remain on the protest sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has been said that arguing against globalization is like
arguing against the law of gravity,'' Annan said. ''But that does
not mean we should accept a law which allows only heavyweights to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ''On the contrary -- we must make globalization an engine that
lifts people out of hardship and misery, not a force that holds
them down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Annan called on the grass-roots groups to join partnerships with
the United Nations like the recently launched Global Compact
collaboration of corporations, U.N. agencies, labor unions and
human rights groups to promote good business practices around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day non-governmental summit is happening ahead of the
Sept. 6-8 U.N. Millennium Summit, where more than 150 world leaders
will converge at U.N. headquarters to try to chart a new course for
the United Nations in the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Hanan Ashrawi, a frequent spokeswoman for the Palestinians,
echoed Annan's call to activists to keep pressuring governments.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must not only shape the vision but articulate the vision,''
she said in a keynote address. ''That's what makes us different.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashrawi said individuals must be willing to take risks as
Palestinians did during the six-year uprising against Israeli
occupation to fight for peace and basic human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe that the human will, the human spirit and ultimately
the decision to take risks to stand up and be counted are what make
a difference in terms of altering realities,'' said Ashrawi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
