<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Authorities identify woman found dead at rest stop  </HEADLINE>
By MELISSA NELSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK (AP) - A woman was found stabbed to death near an
interstate highway rest area whose surveillance cameras were
out-of-service since at least last week, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Video from the cameras could have shown investigators some of
the people who were at the Interstate 40 rest stop at Morrilton
when Kristin Ann Laurite, 25, of Scotch Plains, N.J., stopped there
during the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cameras are focused on the building at the rest area. We
don't know if the surveillance would have picked up the crime, but
it could provide useful information,'' Highway Department spokesman
Randy Ort said. ''It's just extremely unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing was the third at an Arkansas rest area in four
years. After killings in 1996 and 1997, the highway department set
up cameras and posted signs warning of the surveillance as a way to
improve safety.
</P>
<P>
   ''The cameras are still in place and the signs are still up (at
Morrilton),'' Ort said. ''Sometimes those things act as a
deterrent, but we do not have any videotape.''
</P>
<P>
   The equipment was removed and taken to Little Rock last
Wednesday for repair.
</P>
<P>
   Laurite, who was traveling to California, had told her mother
Friday afternoon that she planned to stop somewhere along the way
and sleep in her van, Conway County Sheriff Mark Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   A truck driver found the woman's dogs running loose late
Saturday and called a phone number listed on the dog tags, Flowers
said. The truck driver reached the woman's mother, who said
something must be wrong because the dogs never strayed.
</P>
<P>
   The dogs led state police and sheriff's deputies to the woman's
body, on the bank of a pond near the rest area on the westbound
side of the highway.
</P>
<P>
   Flowers and Ort said there has been vandalism at the rest stop,
and the sheriff said there had been discussions recently about
closing the site. Interstate exits, with services, are nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ''That will be up to the state. They are in charge of the rest
area,'' Flowers said.
</P>
<P>
   Ort said the Morrilton area has had problems ''for quite some
time, as far as vandalism and crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, truck driver Arthur Joe Cotton, 71, of
Sheridan, was shot to death in the bathroom of the Interstate
40-eastbound rest stop at Morrilton. Two half-brothers from West
Virginia were convicted of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   In November 1996, Russell D. Hinkle, 71, of Millstadt, Ill., was
shot and killed after he stopped with his family at a tourist
information center on Interstate 55 near Blytheville. Four
Blytheville teen-agers were convicted of the slayings.
</P>
<P>
   The state Highway Department in 1997 discussed hiring 24-hour
security guards but decided it was too expensive. It opted instead
for the surveillance cameras, which are aimed at the outside of the
restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   No one watches the video, but it is preserved should there be a
reason to review it.
</P>
<P>
   Ort said the Morrilton area was the only one with a broken video
system during the weekend. He said he didn't know how highway
commissioners would react to the incident, though closing the area
would be an option if motorists can't be protected.
</P>
<P>
   ''Safety is very important,'' Ort said.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver said he would take the dogs to the woman's
mother, Flowers said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 2051 </TRAILER>
