<SUBHEAD>
Bush, Gore Tied in Two New Polls
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democrat Al Gore and Republican George W. Bush are locked
in a dead heat in two new presidential polls. The CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of
likely voters showed Bush at 46 percent, Gore at 45 percent, Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader at 3 percent and Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan at 1
percent. A poll by ICR of Media, Pa. showed Gore at 44 percent and Bush at 41
percent among registered voters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
American in Peru To Get New Trial
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- More than four years after hooded military judges
convicted American Lori Berenson of planning a rebel attack, Peru's military
overturned her life sentence and cleared the way for a new, civilian trial,
officials said today. The 30-year-old New York native was found guilty of
treason for allegedly helping Tupac Amaru rebels plan a failed attack on Peru's
Congress.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton, Mubarak To Meet
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ARUSHA, Tanzania (AP) -- President Clinton was due in Cairo to discuss
Mideast peace on Tuesday with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak. He wants
Mubarak's help in talks between Israel and the Palestinians. Clinton was to meet
with Mubarak early Tuesday at the end of a four-day African tour. Earlier,
Clinton and South Africa's Nelson Mandela lectured warring factions from Burundi
on the consequences of the collapse of their own peace talks.
</P>
