Police Question Patsy Ramsey
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- John and Patsy Ramsey's attorney accused a prosecutor today
of turning the couple's first interview with police in two years into a
''fishing expedition'' to prove the couple killed their daughter, JonBenet, in
1996. Attorney L. Lin Wood said prosecutor Michael Kane would not consider other
suspects. A team led by Boulder, Colo., police Chief Mark Beckner questioned
Patsy Ramsey at Wood's Atlanta office for about seven hours. It planned to
question John Ramsey tomorrow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Record-Breaking Dry Spell in Texas
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- With not even a hint of rain to settle the dust, North Texas
spent its 59th day without moisture -- longer than the record-setting dry spell
during the Dust Bowl days of the Depression. Lawns are burned, farmers and
ranchers have lost an estimated $595 million and reservoirs are shrinking fast,
even though rainfall for the year is close to normal. It's not just dry; it's
hot. Today was the year's 36th day of 100-degree temperatures in Dallas-Fort
Worth. The record is 69 days, set in 1980.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
2 Die in Arkansas Campus Shooting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FAYETTEVILLE, Ark. (AP) -- A longtime professor and a graduate student who
had been taking classes for 10 years were shot to death today at the University
of Arkansas in an apparent murder-suicide on the first day of the fall semester,
authorities said. Associate professor John Locke, 67, died in his English
department office in Kimpel Hall. Capt. Brad Bruns identified the other victim
as a graduate student in the comparative literature program, the classes Locke
taught. He said police didn't know of a motive for the shootings or who pulled
the trigger.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Caesareans on the Rise Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Caesarean sections started dropping slowly in the early
1990s after an outcry that American women undergo too many -- but now they're on
the rise again. With Caesareans inching back up to 22 percent of U.S. births,
the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists is issuing new
guidelines to reduce unnecessary C-sections.
</P>
