<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urologist charged with murdering her parents  </HEADLINE>
AP Photo
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATHAM, N.J. (AP) - By all accounts, Idella Kathleen Hagen was
in the middle of a brilliant career in medicine. A Harvard Medical
School graduate, Hagen became the first female resident to
specialize in urology at a Massachusetts hospital, and later broke
ground as the first woman to head a urology division at any
hospital in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, however, Hagen abandoned the medical profession
for reasons unknown and went to the U.S. Virgin Islands, officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities are delving into her past for answers after charging
Hagen, 54, with smothering her elderly parents in their beds in the
home she had shared with them for a month.
</P>
<P>
   Morris County authorities declined to speculate on a motive for
the alleged slayings Monday and would not say if Hagen had
confessed. Superior Court Judge Reginald Stanton refused to make a
probable cause affidavit in Hagen's case public, saying it
contained prejudicial information against Hagen.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen was arrested Saturday after calling police to the modest
home with an overgrown yard she shared with parents Idella Hagen,
92, and James Hagen, 86, and reported they had died. The parents
were found in their pajamas in their twin beds, and had been dead
for at least several days, said Capt. Christopher Linne, spokesman
for the Morris County Prosecutor's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The parents ''had probably the normal ailments people of that
age would have,'' but were not dying of a specific illness, Linne
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors who had recently spoken to Hagen said she was
depressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember suggesting that she see a therapist, and she said
'no,''' neighbor Laura Tucker told The Star-Ledger of Newark. ''But
later she called back and asked for the phone number.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagen had told Tucker and her husband, Scott, that she was
having a hard time coping after a recent divorce and was unsure
what to do about her career.
</P>
<P>
   ''I suggested she go to an employment agency. She sighed 'Oh
boy,''' Scott Tucker said. ''The feeling was, she didn't think
she'd get a great career by visiting an employment agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagen began her career in medicine at Rutgers' Medical School,
which is now the Robert Wood Johnson Medical School, part of the
University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   She transferred to Harvard Medical School in 1971 and graduated
in 1973 under the name Kathleen Hagen Cook, Harvard spokeswoman
Judith Montminy said. She then spent six years as a resident at
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, becoming the first woman
to specialize in urology, hospital spokeswoman Michelle Marcella
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, she spent six months as an instructor in surgery at
Harvard Medical School, then returned to serve a clinical
fellowship in surgery at Massachusetts General, Marcella said.
</P>
<P>
   She moved on to Rutgers Medical School, where she became chief
of the division of urology in 1982, the first woman to head a
urology division at an American medical school, UMDNJ spokeswoman
Susan Preston said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 she went to part-time status and in 1992 took an unpaid
leave from the job, Preston said. School records do not list a
reason for the leave, Preston said.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say she went to the U.S. Virgin Islands and managed
a hotel that has since gone out of business. She moved in with her
parents in July, Linne said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's obviously a tragedy. It's obviously a shock,'' Hagen's
ex-husband, William Tyrrell of Stuart, Fla., said on Monday. He
said he had not been in contact with Hagen and declined further
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen is being held at the Morris County Correctional Facility
in Morris Township on $2.5 million bail. Her arraignment is
scheduled for Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 2138 </TRAILER>
