<HEADLINE> Georgia Suspends Receiver Greer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Georgia suspended senior receiver Michael
Greer for the first five games of the season on Monday for
violating team rules.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Donnan did not specify the reason for the suspension
just five days before the 10th-ranked Bulldogs will open the season
at home against defending I-AA national champion Georgia Southern.
</P>
<P>
   ''Taking disciplinary action on any player is always
unpleasant,'' Donnan said in a statement. ''However, abiding by
team rules and policies are part of being a member of this football
program. Michael understands that he made a mistake and is willing
to pay the price. And I'm confident he'll still be a valuable
member of our team when he returns.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer, a three-year letterman from Athens, has 49 receptions for
738 yards and five touchdowns in his career. He also has returned
38 punts for 299 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made a mistake and for that I apologize to the coaches and
my teammates,'' Greer said. ''I'm ready to pay the price and work
my way back so I can make a contribution to the goals that have
been set by this team.''
</P>
<P>
   While Greer is one of the team's most experienced receivers,
Georgia should have little trouble filling his spot.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Edwards was the top receiver as a freshman with 53
receptions for 772 yards and nine touchdowns. The Bulldogs also
have a talented 1999 class of pass-catchers: Durell Robinson and
Reggie Brown, who sat out last season because of academic problems,
and redshirt freshmen Michael Johnson and Damien Gary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
