<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nader Petition Theft Casts Doubts  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARAMIE, Wyo. (AP) -- Ralph Nader barely met Monday's deadline
for filing to get on Wyoming's general election ballot, but the
theft of nearly 650 petition signatures on his behalf is casting
doubt on whether the Green Party presidential hopeful's name will
appear at all.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Nader's ballot status is also in question in
neighboring South Dakota because he missed the June 20 filing
deadline. But his lawyers told a federal judge Monday that he
should be put on the ballot anyway because the early filing
deadline amounts to an unconstitutional restriction on the ability
of third-party candidates to collect the required signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Nader failed to file the 2,602 signatures required of
independent candidates.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Charles Kornmann said he would issue a
ruling Tuesday, the deadline for the secretary of state to tell
counties what information should be on ballots for the Nov. 7
election.
</P>
<P>
   In Wyoming, someone walked off with a clipboard full of
signatures after being handed it to sign at a Laramie restaurant
last Thursday, according to Nader volunteer Roberta
Harper-McIntosh.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we had those signatures, we'd be a little more
comfortable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters turned in about 4,000 signatures to state election
officials just one minute before Monday evening's filing deadline,
said Deputy Secretary of State Pat Arp.
</P>
<P>
   They had hoped to deliver between 5,000 and 6,000 -- just in
case.
</P>
<P>
   The Secretary of State's Office requires the signatures of 2
percent of the voting population, or 3,484 certified signatures, to
put a candidate or party on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will begin the petition-checking process right away and
should know within a few days,'' Arp said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2145 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Environmentalist Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIA PARRA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACAPULCO, Mexico (AP) -- A peasant leader and award-winning
environmentalist was convicted on drug and weapons charges Monday
and sentenced to six years in prison. Human rights and
environmental groups immediately denounced the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities charged that Rodolfo Montiel and his supporters were
protecting marijuana plants and that he and Teodoro Cabrera Garcia
admitted belonging to guerrilla groups.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel has claimed the charges were lodged in retaliation for
his work as leader of a rural ecological group in Mexico's Pacific
coast state of Guerrero.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera Garcia received a 10-year sentence on drug and illegal
arms possession charges Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We profoundly regret what happened today,'' said Cristian
Rojas, education coordinator for Amnesty International's Mexico
office. ''This represents a step backward in the process of
obtaining justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas told The Associated Press that the court's action will
provoke ''international pressure even greater than what has already
existed.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We will pursue this case until they are freed,'' said Rojas,
who noted that Amnesty's Washington office already has petitioned
Mexico's President-elect Vicente Fox to intervene. Fox takes office
on Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel and Cabrera Garcia were detained on May 2, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Montiel's group forms human chains to stop logging trucks from
passing through Guerrero. He is widely considered by environmental
groups to be a fearless crusader for trees. He and his supporters
believe old-growth forests in Guerrero are being excessively
logged.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the 44-year-old Montiel was one of seven recipients
worldwide of the $125,000 Goldman prize, given by the San
Francisco-based Goldman Environmental Foundation in recognition for
efforts to preserve the environment.
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty, which has declared Montiel a prisoner of conscience,
and Mexico's Human Rights Center claim that both Montiel and
Cabrera Garcia have suffered brutal torture at the hands of police
trying to extract confessions from them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2145 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressGene Sherman
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIOUX CITY, Iowa (AP) -- Gene Sherman, a Sioux City sports
broadcaster, died Sunday in South Sioux City, Neb., following a
lengthy illness with cancer. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman was the voice of the Sioux City Soos baseball team in
his early broadcasting years, then he became known widely as the
sports director for KMNS Radio and KCAU-TV.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1999, he was inducted into the Greater Siouxland
Athletic Association Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman received the Iowa Sportscaster of the Year Award in
1982, the distinguished service award from the Iowa High School
Athletic Directors Association.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman was the voice of the Morningside College Chiefs from
1950-65. He took over the Briar Cliff College basketball
play-by-play duties in 1975 and continued broadcasting the games
through the 1996-97 season.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Sioux City Nov. 13, 1921. He graduated in 1940
from Central High School and later the University of Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   A friend, Sheldon Singer, had taken a job as the first program
director at radio station KCOM, which signed on the air in 1949.
Sherman tagged along and helped Singer broadcast Sioux City Soos
baseball games. Not long after, Sherman went to work full-time for
the station, which became KMNS.
</P>
<P>
   He started broadcasting on television in 1956 as the host of a
weekly bowling show. He joined the station full-time in 1959, and
was named sports director at KCAU in 1961. Sherman, who was known
as ''Coach,'' retired in 1985. He also broadcast sports for KTIV
until 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2146 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Claims Wiley Off Waivers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Desperate for help on the defensive line, the
Atlanta Falcons claimed former Carolina Panthers defensive end
Chuck Wiley off waivers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley, who was released Sunday, started 16 games last year as
the Panthers' right defensive end. He made 67 tackles but had no
sacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have major concerns with their pass rush. Starting
right end Brady Smith has been sidelined with a pulled groin for
two weeks. He missed practice again Monday and is doubtful for
Sunday's season opener against the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's injury forced Atlanta to start defensive tackles Ed
Jasper and Travis Hall at left end in the last two preseason games.
The picture was further clouded, though, when Jasper twisted his
right knee and ankle in a 31-20 preseason win at Jacksonville last
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Kerney, still listed as the Falcons starter at left end,
has played the last two games on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley, who had no sacks in 1999, lost his job when Carolina
signed Chuck Smith, second on the Falcons' career sacks list, to a
five-year, $21 million contract over six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through his rookie training camp, Wiley won a starting
job. He missed the entire 1998 season, though, after rupturing his
Achilles' tendon in a preseason game at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Wiley, a third-round draft choice out of Louisiana State in
1998, started three years for the Tigers and accumulated 19 sacks.
</P>
<P>
   To make room for Wiley, Atlanta cut defensive end Chris White,
claimed off waivers only four days ago from Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also signed former Chicago Bears cornerback Terry
Cousin, who started nine games on the right side last year and
finished with 52 tackles, two interceptions, one fumble recovery
and one forced fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Cousin replaces Michael Booker, who was cut Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Evan Pilgrim was released Monday when the Falcons claimed
Chris Banks off waivers from Denver. Banks started one of the 16
games he played in last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2148 </TRAILER>
