<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge: Take Lindland to Sydney  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Greco-Roman wrestler Matt Lindland is back on the
U.S. Olympic team, and Keith Sieracki is off it. For now.
</P>
<P>
   A judge ordered the U.S. Olympic Committee on Monday to take
Lindland to the Sydney Games, the latest reversal in a lengthy
dispute that has bounced between arbitrators and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland lost to Sieracki in the 167&AMP;frac12;-pound class at the
Greco-Roman wrestling trials in June and in a final arbitrator's
decision last week.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. District Judge B. Zagel ruled Monday that an
arbitration ruling that led to a rematch -- with Lindland winning --
was upheld by an appeals court and should settle the matter.
</P>
<P>
   A second arbitration held in Colorado was decided in Sieracki's
favor on Thursday, but Zagel said it has not been confirmed by the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an old proposition -- judges trump arbitrators when they
have jurisdiction,'' said Zagel, who stayed his order until 3 p.m.
Tuesday to give the USOC time to go to the 7th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   USOC attorney Irving B. Levinson said he would consult with the
committee before determining whether the ruling would be appealed.
Meanwhile, Sieracki is trying to get an order from a federal court
in Colorado upholding the arbitration that went his way.
</P>
<P>
   The wrangling goes back to the Olympic trials in June, when
Sieracki beat Lindland 2-1 on a referee's decision after overtime.
Lindland protested the match that decided the best-of-three series,
saying Sieracki tripped him, in violation of wrestling rules.
</P>
<P>
   After Lindland's protests were denied twice by USA Wrestling, he
appealed to an arbitrator, who ruled there should be a rematch.
Lindland beat Sieracki 8-0 in the Aug. 14 rematch.
</P>
<P>
   Sieracki then filed his own appeal. But hours later, the 7th
Circuit decided that Lindland, not Sieracki, should get the Olympic
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys were girding for the possibility of more court action
in the tangled case.
</P>
<P>
   Sieracki was rated as the top wrestler for 2000-01 by Team USA
and USA Wrestling. But Lindland, who is working out with the U.S.
team, contends he should have been chosen.
</P>
<P>
   The official deadline to submit rosters for next month's Olympic
games was Friday, but the USOC took the weekend to make a decision.
USOC attorney Levinson argued that, because of the deadline, the
question was now out of USOC's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Lindland's attorney, Kevin B. Duff, said there was still plenty
of time to make a change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
