<HEADLINE> Yankees' Knoblauch's Knee Looks OK  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A magnetic resonance imaging test on New York
Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch's left knee showed no
damage, manager Joe Torre said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's fine. He's taking a couple of days off,'' Torre said.
''But he's had a tough year physically.''
</P>
<P>
   The MRI was done Saturday after Knoblauch left his first minor
league rehab game Friday night in Kissimmee, Fla., after being hit
by a pitch on the outside of his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Torre anticipated seeing Knoblauch on Friday night when the
Yankees return home to play Minnesota, or soon thereafter. ''It
might be the first or the third or the fourth,'' he said. ''We
don't know yet.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I'm planning on having him back,'' Torre added. ''He's
still going to be a benefit for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's right elbow has bothered him for the past month. An
MRI earlier this month confirmed a previous diagnosis that he has
tendinitis and inflammation in the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   He said his elbow has not improved since starting his rehab at
the Yankees' player development center in Tampa, Fla., two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch has not played second base for the Yankees since July
24. In 78 games with New York, he's hitting .291 with five home
runs and 22 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Sojo, who was acquired in a trade with Pittsburgh on Aug.
7, is playing second in Knoblauch's absence. Sojo was 2-for-4 with
an RBI in Sunday's win in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sojo is such a good player to have,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Ramiro Mendoza threw 40 pitches off the mound for
the first time Monday in Tampa as part of his throwing program and
reported no problems. Mendoza is on the disabled list with
tendinitis of his right shoulder. He's pitched in 14 games,
including nine starts, this season, with a 7-4 record and 4.25 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll see him Friday,'' Torre said. ''If everything works
well, he'll continue his throwing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
