<DOCNO> APW20000828.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sailboat Wreck Suit Goes To Court  </HEADLINE>
By BRUCE SMITH
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Libby Cornett choked back tears Monday
describing when she finally heard the distress call sent by the
sailboat Morning Dew after it wrecked on a stormy winter night in
1997, killing her husband, two sons and a younger cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ''I heard Daniel. I heard Daniel saying 'mayday,' '' she
testified, recalling her son's voice. ''I realized at that moment
they didn't have to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cornett, 49, of Hiltons, Va.; sons, Michael Paul, 16,
and Daniel, 13; and cousin Bobby Hurd, 14, of Mountain City, Tenn.,
all died. Their families now are suing the Coast Guard for $35
million.
</P>
<P>
   They might have been saved, but the Coast Guard operated as
''stumbling, bumbling fools,'' the families' lawyer, Gedney Howe,
said as the trial opened in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cornett has said that before she heard the tape of the
mayday call, it was easier to accept it as an accident. Now, she
says, ''It's a torment to us every passing day.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge David Norton will have to decide when the
search began. The Coast Guard is under no obligation to conduct a
search, but once one starts, the agency must do so in a reasonable
manner. The families contend that did not happen.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Cornett's mayday came at 2:17 a.m. on Dec. 29. The
sailboat had hit one of the Charleston Harbor jetties as a storm
raged.
</P>
<P>
   A Coast Guard petty officer tried to return the call but got no
reply. Later, the officer said he did not hear the word mayday.
</P>
<P>
   Another static-filled radio call came a few minutes later. The
officer said no message could be made out. The families said that
also came from the Morning Dew.
</P>
<P>
   About four hours later, a crewman on a ship coming into
Charleston said he heard a cry for help. A pilot boat returned to
search the area but found nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard did not dispatch its units until about 11 a.m.,
when two of the boys' bodies were found on a nearby beach.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case is not about what the Coast Guard should have
done,'' said government lawyer Debra Kossow.
</P>
<P>
   The response to the voices in the water started before the Coast
Guard was even called and did not constitute a Coast Guard search,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Howe, however, said, ''There is certainly strong evidence in
this instance the harbor pilots responded at least partially on
behalf of the Coast Guard.''
</P>
<P>
   The boys who washed up on the beach showed faint signs of life.
Had the Coast Guard moved more quickly five hours earlier, they
might have been saved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the pilot boat reported it found nothing, however, the
Coast Guard aborted the search ''recklessly and without the
slightest degree of care,'' Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Cornett did not know about the distress calls until almost
three months after the wreck and neither did the state Natural
Resources Department, which investigates wrecks of recreational
craft.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Pritcher, the agent investigating for Natural Resources,
testified initial logs from the Coast Guard did not mention the
calls. The Coast Guard said at the time there was nothing the
officer perceived as a distress call.
</P>
<P>
   ''They tried to cover it up,'' Howe told the judge. ''The lied
about it because they knew it was important.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard finally released details of the calls because
they knew they would have to respond to a request under the Freedom
of Information Act filed by The Boating News, Howe said.
</P>
<P>
   In its review of the accident, the National Transportation
Safety Board said Cornett's ''failure to adequately assess, prepare
for and respond to the known risks of the journey into the open
ocean'' most likely caused the crash. Cornett was severely fatigued
and suffering from hypothermia, investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the board added: ''Contributing to the loss of life in
this accident was the substandard performance of U.S. Coast Guard
Group Charleston in initiating a search-and-rescue response to the
accident.'' ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Coast Guard Search and Rescue:
http://www.uscg.mil/hq/g-o/g-opr/sar.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2218 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
