<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mariners' Meche May Be Out for Year  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Gil Meche, who came out of a rehabilitation start
at Class A Everett after one inning, probably will not pitch again
this season, Seattle Mariners manager Lou Piniella said Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we'll probably shut him down for the rest of the
year,'' Piniella said. ''His arm feels real tired and real heavy.
We had to shut him down last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Meche lasted only one inning in Sunday's minor league game.
</P>
<P>
   Meche, 21, was supposed to be a mainstay in the Mariners'
rotation this season, but has been limited to 15 starts. He has
been on the disabled list twice this season with a strained right
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Meche made his last start for the Mariners July 4 in Anaheim,
going 5 2-3 innings in a 7-6 loss. He was put on the DL July 31.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella had hoped to add him to his rotation in September.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a little bit of a longshot for us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella said Meche told Mariners officials he had similar
shoulder problems before he signed with the team in 1996. It was
diagnosed as tendinitis then.
</P>
<P>
   Meche has a 4-4 record with a 3.78 ERA in 85 2-3 innings for the
Mariners this season. As a rookie with Seattle last season, he was
8-4 with a 4.73 ERA in 15 starts after being called up in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2235 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000828.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NFL Camps Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   It took 11 games last season for Pittsburgh to
replace Kordell
Stewart as starting quarterback. The Steelers aren't even waiting
until the first game this year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coach Bill Cowher issued a three-paragraph statement Monday
saying Kent Graham, who previously lost starting jobs with Arizona
and the New York Giants, will start Sunday's season opener against
the Baltimore Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just going to go out and play relaxed, because that's how
I play the best,'' Graham said. ''I know in this game, or any game,
if things aren't going well and the coach feels he'll need a spark,
he'll make a change. I don't think that's different from any other
team across the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham began the 1997 season as starting quarterback with the
Cardinals and with the Giants last year, but couldn't keep his job
either time.
</P>
<P>
   The decision caught Stewart by surprise. Stewart began the
preseason with the quarterback's job to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't say I was shook up, but was kind of stunned a little
bit,'' Stewart said. ''At the same time, I understood. You can't do
anything but accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 18 months after signing a $27 million contract extension,
Stewart faces an uncertain future with a team that couldn't wait
any longer for him to play his way out of a two-year slump.
</P>
<P>
   Graham was 31-of-57 for 334 yards, three touchdowns and one
interception during the preseason. Stewart was 19-of-55 for 238
yards, one touchdown and two interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not flattered, let's be honest,'' Stewart said. ''The one
thing I hate most is leaving it up to the coaches. When you leave
it up to the coaches, you never know what kind of decision they'll
make.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you outright go out and outperform whomever it is you are
competing against, hands down ... but I left it up to the coaches.
I'm more upset with myself than anybody else because I had the
opportunity and I didn't seize it.''
Bengals:
</P>
<P>
   Running back Corey Dillon missed practice following his weekend
arrest in a Seattle suburb after his wife was assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon, 25, also did not tell the team about Saturday's arrest.
Players were off Saturday and Sunday, and Dillon told the team he
would be late returning.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the former University of Washington standout was
arrested Saturday afternoon after officers responded to a domestic
violence complaint at a Federal Way, Wash., address.
</P>
<P>
   When officers arrived, they found Dillon's 23-year-old wife
bleeding from the mouth in front of the house. Dillon was in the
driveway, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon was booked into the King County jail for investigation of
fourth-degree assault, but later released.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the couple was in a car when Dillon struck his wife,
who was driving. She got out of the car and walked one block to the
address where police were summoned.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cincinnati claimed safety Chris Carter and receiver
Danny Farmer off waivers, and waived receiver James Hundon and
safety Lawrence Wright.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals also extended the contracts of offensive linemen
Brock Gutierrez through 2002, and Jamain Stephens through 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Signed to the practice squad were JoJuan Armour, a second-year
safety from Miami of Ohio; LaVell Boyd, a rookie receiver from
Louisville; Mike Doughty, a second-year offensive tackle from Notre
Dame; Sirr Parker, a first-year cornerback from Texas A&AMP;M, and
Roger Roesler, a rookie offensive guard from Texas.
Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Thomas Jones will start at running back in the season
opener against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Vince Tobin decided Monday to move Jones, the No. 7
overall pick from Virginia, ahead of Michael Pittman, who started
all four preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   The move could mean rookie running backs will start for both
teams in the opener. The Giants will likely start their top draft
pick, Ron Dayne, chosen 11th overall.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, the second running back selected in the draft, shrugged
off the starting role as no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't matter whether you start or not,'' he said. ''What
matters is at the end of the game how many yards you have, how many
big plays you have. I'd rather be out there making big plays and
scoring some touchdowns rather than starting just to be starting.''
</P>
<P>
   In the preseason, Jones rushed for 100 yards in 31 carries and
two touchdowns. He also caught six passes for 40 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona also claimed second-year defensive lineman Russell Davis
off waivers from the Chicago Bears, and waived running back
Clarence Williams, who spent all of his 1999 rookie season on the
Cardinals' practice squad.
Vikings:
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Cris Dishman signed a three-year deal that will pay
him about $500,000 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year veteran who played for Houston, Washington and
Kansas City, was waived by the Chiefs, who were deep in
cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Dishman, whose first workout with the Vikings is Wednesday, will
play in the opener against Chicago on Sunday, coach Dennis Green
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dishman, a two-time Pro Bowler, has been a full-time starter
since 1990 and has 42 career interceptions. He had five
interceptions and 84 tackles last year.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota released linebacker Pete Bercich and replaced him with
linebacker Jim Nelson, who was waived by Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings also signed five players to their practice squad:
tight end Matt Cercone; quarterback Billy Cockerham; tackle Jay
Humphrey; defensive back Don Morgan, and guard Nick O'Brien.
Cowboys:
</P>
<P>
   Dallas signed cornerback Phillippi Sparks to a five-year
contract and expects him to play in the season opener against
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Kareem Larrimore, a rookie cornerback expected to start,
struggled in preseason games, sixth-year safety Charlie Williams
will miss at least two games recovering from offseason knee
surgery, and Kevin Smith retired.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks spent the past seven seasons with the Giants, but hinted
he might retire and didn't sign before training camp.
</P>
<P>
   To make room, the Cowboys waived linebacker Chris Bordano,
acquired from New Orleans in an offseason trade for cornerback
Kevin Mathis. Sparks got a $1.5 million signing bonus and will make
about $500,000 this season.
Browns:
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Alexander, a starting defensive end last season for
Cleveland, was placed on the reserve injured list and won't play
for the Browns again.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is not going to play again,'' coach Chris Palmer said. ''He
has a sprained right ankle and you cannot waive an injured player,
but we presented Derrick with several options. I feel good that he
will be with us in some capacity. Maybe even tomorrow morning.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be as an assistant coach.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Alexander, selected in the first round of the
1995 draft by Minnesota, signed with Cleveland as a free agent last
year after four seasons with the Vikings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
