<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazios reveal 10 years of income tax records  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - After months of prodding by journalists and his
Democratic opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio on Monday gave reporters
access to a decade's worth of tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman and his wife Patricia, who works part-time as a
nurse, made about $150,000 in 1999. At first glance, the federal
and state tax returns dating back to 1990 didn't appear to contain
anything unusual, which prompted a question: what took so long?
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, who entered the U.S. Senate race against Hillary Rodham
Clinton in May after New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani backed out as
the Republican candidate, had promised since the early days of his
campaign to release his tax returns by the end of the summer.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, he was dogged in appearances around the state
by Democratic Party operatives - including various people in Uncle
Sam suits dubbed ''Tax Man'' - who barked at the candidate to
release the tax information.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kauffmann, a spokesman for the state Democratic Party,
said Lazio still hasn't explained why it took three months to
releases his tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time for Mr. Lazio to stop playing games and start
playing straight,'' Kauffmann said.
</P>
<P>
   While reporters were not able to take copies of the Lazios'
federal and state tax returns, they were permitted to review them
and were invited to pore over the figures for as long as necessary
- some stayed for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio was not at campaign headquarters in Manhattan when the tax
forms were provided.
</P>
<P>
   The financial reports showed the Lazios with income from his
salary as a congressman, her work as a nurse and modest returns on
investments. The couple also reported income from the rental of a
vacation home on Fire Island.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, their income was $152,000, for which they paid $22,341
in taxes. The couple made $2,422 in charitable donations, although
the recipients of their largesse were not itemized. In 10 years of
marriage, the most the Lazios made in any year was $159,258, in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's tax filings also reflect a diverse investment strategy
over the past few years, with stock dealings involving Computer
Associates, Compaq, McDonald's, Nike, Halliburton, Monsanto, Sun
Microsystems, Johnson &AMP; Johnson and Quick &AMP; Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission announced last week that
it would take no action following a probe into lucrative stock
option trading by Lazio in Quick &AMP; Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Records showed that Lazio spent about $2,300 in early August
1997 for options on stock of Quick &AMP; Reilly, a Long Island-based
brokerage firm. On Sept. 17, 1997, the firm was bought by the Fleet
Financial Group. Lazio sold his stock options that same day for
almost $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Quick and Christopher C. Quick, former senior executives
of Quick &AMP; Reilly, who along with other company executives have
donated at least $35,000 to Lazio's campaigns since 1995, said they
had never discussed the company's stock or possible sale with the
congressman. Lazio denied any insider knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   In the early years of their marriage, Patricia Lazio's salary
was higher than her husband's income as a Suffolk County
legislator. In 1990 and 1991, he earned about $40,000 annually,
while she earned $44,000 and $52,000, respectively, for her work as
a nurse at Veteran's Administration hospitals in Manhattan and
Northport
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, the Clintons reported adjusted gross income of
$416,039. She had no immediate comment on the release of Lazio's
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Clinton grazed friendly political ground at three
campaign stops in the heavily Democratic Bronx. She greeted
commuters at a subway stop and later campaigned with congressional
candidate Larry Seabrook at Concourse Village housing complex near
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Seabrook caught the spirit of the event when he told 150 soggy
supporters huddled under umbrellas, ''There are no more loyal
Democratic voters that the voters in Concourse Village.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also visited a senior citizens' center in the
Williamsbridge section and was applauded for her promise to include
prescription drugs in Medicare benefits and give tax credits to
families who take care of senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In between the Bronx campaign stops, Clinton spoke to the state
AFL-CIO convention in Manhattan, receiving a standing ovation from
800 union members when she pledged to fight for an increased
minimum wage and equal pay for women.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not just a woman's issue,'' she said. ''It's a family
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was endorsed by the state AFL-CIO last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-28-00 2306 </TRAILER>
