<HEADLINE> Britain, Sierra Leone Captors Talk  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- British officials have begun
talking to a renegade military faction that has taken 11 British
soldiers captive, and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Monday
he expects the soldiers to be released soon.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers, held since Friday, have been in periodic radio
contact, including a discussion Sunday, officials said. The captors
in this west African nation also have been in contact with the
British.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have opened up dialogue with the group holding them through
their leader,'' Lt. Cmdr. Tony Cramp, a spokesman for the British
force, said. He said the British have communicated with a fighter
known as Brigadier Kalla, one of the top leaders of the group,
known as the West Side Boys.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard confirmed that talks
were under way and said the captives are doing well.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said earlier that ''there are expectations that they will
be released and progress will be made.'' He said he hoped the
soldiers would be released ''in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   The captured British soldiers were stationed at Benguema, about
25 miles east of the capital Freetown, where British instructors
are training Sierra Leonean army recruits under a bilateral
agreement. They disappeared Friday in an area occupied by the West
Side Boys.
</P>
<P>
   The British troops are not part of the U.N. peacekeeping mission
in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Rebels from the Revolutionary United Front reignited Sierra
Leone's nine-year civil war in May by seizing about 500 U.N.
peacekeepers and keeping 233 others surrounded for 2&AMP;frac12; months,
severely embarrassing the United Nations and prompting a
reassessment of the U.N. mission.
</P>
<P>
   Annan called Friday for a beefed-up U.N. force of 20,500
peacekeepers to help government troops regain control of the
country from the rebels. He was responding to a Security Council
resolution adopted earlier this month to increase the 13,000-member
force.
</P>
<P>
   Annan told reporters Monday that the United Nations is taking
steps ''to strengthen the peacekeepers, to give them the tools they
need to be able to defend themselves and their mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports in several British newspapers said the government had
sent an SAS special forces team to Sierra Leone to stand by if
needed for a rescue. Two police hostage negotiators reportedly also
went.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
