<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Promotes Prescription Drug Plan  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Al Gore told senior citizens Monday
that ''you deserve better'' from the government in help paying for
prescription drugs and said he's the only presidential candidate
with a plan to provide it.
</P>
<P>
   In campaign appearances and TV ads, Democrat Gore and Republican
rival George W. Bush hammered at the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do invite you to compare and contrast the plans we have put
forward,'' said Gore. ''Don't take it from me, go check it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush aides dismissed the vice president's proposal for a drug
benefit under Medicare as ''old-style'' big government but also
said the Texas governor would spell out details for his own
proposal soon, a tacit admission that Gore has scored on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, asked about the subject in Texas, praised a bipartisan
commission's plan that he said would allow senior citizens ''to
pick and choose amongst a variety of plans, all of which will
include prescription drugs.'' He has spoken favorably of the idea
of subsidizing insurance companies to provide drug coverage for
low-income senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent the day hearing heart-wrenching stories from elderly
people who are unable to keep up with health care bills, and
offered stories of his own family's health.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Flatt, 77, told Gore he pays $1,800 a year in
prescription drug costs, also must care for a disabled son and
desperately needs a prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've been praying for one, not only for myself, but for those
who are worse off than myself,' he said. Gore told him, ''You are
carrying a bigger load than you should.''
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people here want to hug you,'' Gore said, and he did
just that.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know I won't always be the most exciting politician, but I
will work for you every day and I will never let you down,'' said
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Gore would spend the week focusing on health care, an
issue he used effectively in the primaries to defeat fellow
Democrat Bill Bradley and one that has seemed to help in recent
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The race between Gore and Bush, meanwhile, remains very close,
according to a CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of likely voters released
Monday. Bush had 46 percent and Gore 45 percent, with Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader at 3 percent and Reform Party hopeful Pat
Buchanan at 1 percent -- a dead heat given the margin of error of
plus or minus 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   En route to New Mexico to tout his plan to expand health
coverage to all children, Gore said he was ''ready'' and ''eager''
for a spirited discussion with Bush as voters begin to pay
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the gamble I took to talk about specifics is paying
off,'' he told reporters aboard Air Force Two. ''I'm feeling a lot
of enthusiasm in the response. We're now entering the heart of the
campaign where people feel they have a right to expect the
candidates to deal with the specifics of the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore again criticized Bush's lack of policy detail.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not about momentum, it's about substance. I think the
best substance in the end turns out to be the best politics. That,
in the view of some, is quaint,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has offered a 10-year, $253 billion package that would
include a prescription drug benefit in the Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett's take on that: ''Al Gore today is
proposing a nationalized drug plan that makes the federal
government the dispenser, similar to Hillary Clinton's attempt to
nationalize health care in 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore told his audience in Florida, ''I believe it is time to
tell every senior in the country that we have come to the point
where we can improve Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of Gore's argument is the idea that medical
breakthroughs have brought new treatments into play but many are
beyond the means of fixed-income senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Touring a pharmacy and speaking with elderly people at a
round-table, Gore heard story after story of just that situation.
</P>
<P>
   Myrtle Jennings, 82, told him she suffers from heart troubles
and high blood pressure, as well as arthritis. She's currently
skipping her pain medication to pay for other drugs, she told Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''God bless you,'' said Gore. ''I'll fight for you.''
</P>
<P>
   He also renewed his criticism of the big pharmaceutical
companies, which he said are so powerful ''they have the ability to
dictate the prices.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said his mother-in-law's arthritis medicine
costs $108 a month while the same medication from a veterinarian
would cost $37.80.
</P>
<P>
   ''Don't you think that ought to be changed?'' Gore asked.
''Don't you think we ought to lower the price for seniors''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee weighed in with new television
spots blasting Gore's proposal, and the Democratic National
Committee announced it would run new ads as well.
</P>
<P>
   Gore closed his campaign day with a noisy rally for several
thousand backers in Albuquerque, N.M., sounding standard campaign
themes and taking credit for the economy. ''This election is not a
reward for past performance,'' he said. ''We have to be willing to
make the hard choices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-28-00 2318 </TRAILER>
