<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-28 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haitian Lawmakers Take Office  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL NORTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Fending off international criticism
of their election, lawmakers from Haiti's Lavalas Family party took
office Monday and cemented former President Jean-Bertrand
Aristide's control over Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Incumbents from opposition parties boycotted the session to
protest the disputed election, which was held in three stages in
May, June and July.
</P>
<P>
   Senators chose Sen. Yvon Neptune, spokesman of Aristide's
Lavalas Family party, to be president of the upper house. Lower
house members chose Sainvoyis Pascal, 71, their eldest member, as
acting president.
</P>
<P>
   Aristide's party won 18 of 19 upper-house and 72 of 82
lower-house seats in the election.
</P>
<P>
   An Organization of American States election observation team
objected to the method used to determine which Senate candidates
should have gone to a second, run-off round. The United States and
the European Union have threatened to suspend aid if Haiti does not
amend the results.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of counting the votes of all candidates for Senate
seats, electoral officials only counted the top four contenders.
Opposition parties have accused President Rene Preval of having
rigged the election to favor the Lavalas Family.
</P>
<P>
   ''The senators were elected unconstitutionally,'' said
Jean-Claude Bajeux, a human rights activist and election observer.
''The constitution is in jeopardy and with it the civil rights of
Haitians.''
</P>
<P>
   International financial institutions have put about $400 million
on hold until Monday's installation, but it was unclear whether
they will accept its legitimacy. About 60 percent of Haiti's $800
million annual budget comes from such.
</P>
<P>
   Haiti had been without a legislature since January 1999, when
Preval locked lawmakers out of Parliament to end an 18-month power
struggle with opposition parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
