<HEADLINE> Jordan Ends Tournament Affiliation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. (AP) -- Michael Jordan is ending his affiliation
with a charity golf tournament that has carried his name since
1988, and will start a similar event in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   The Michael Jordan Celebrity Golf Classic, which benefits the
Ronald McDonald houses in North Carolina, will continue in
Greenville in 20001 under a to-be-determined name.
</P>
<P>
   ''This event has become well-established due to the work of
tournament officials and volunteers, as well as the support of
sponsors and celebrities,'' Jordan said in a written statement
released Monday. ''So I felt confident that this was a good a time
as any for me to try my hand at another such event.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the Bahamas event in January, the Michael Jordan
Celebrity Invitational, are making a $300,000 donation to the state
Ronald McDonald houses, said Bill Freelove, chairman of the
Greenville tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is happening is a win-win for the tournament,'' Freelove
said. ''We're thankful Michael has been so generous giving his time
as well as his money.''
</P>
<P>
   The local tournament started in 1984 to build Greenville's
Ronald McDonald House. Jordan participated in the tournament the
next year and agreed to lend his name three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan have given hundreds of thousands of dollars to the
charity.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 tournament had nine major corporate sponsors. All have
verbally committed to supporting the event in the future, said
Emily Faulkner, an event organizer.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 event raised $300,000 for the charity.
</P>
<P>
   The new Jordan tournament, at the Ocean Club on Paradise Island
in the Bahamas, will be a four-day charity event with 36 celebrity
golfers. Organizers are negotiating television coverage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
